<HEADLINE> Opium War Film Premieres in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The premiere of "the Opium War,"
 a Chinese film epic depicting Britain's opium-peddling and the
ceding of Hong Kong, was staged here tonight.
</P>
<P>
The 140-minute film that shows history through real people
tells the audience that in June 1839 the Chinese Emperor's
Special Envoy Lin Zexu confiscated and burned over 20,000 cases of
 opium from British traders.
</P>
<P>
Thus, with support from Queen Victoria, the British parliament
agreed to launch the invasion war against China, with 271 pros
against 262 cons in voting, and occupied Hong Kong later, the
film says.
</P>
<P>
The film also shows how the Chinese people heroically fought
back against the British aggressors in the last century. Its
shooting took seven months and cost about 15 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the premiere ceremony in the Hong Kong Convention
and Exhibition Center, first Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region Tung Chee Hwa said the screening is
of special significance today when Hong Kong's handover is
nearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
