<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Big Three Narrows Gap with Japanese Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Big Three U.S. auto makers
last year narrowed their productivity gap with Japanese rivals in
North America, the Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
Largely due to their improved vehicle design, General Motors
Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. all made improvement in
efficiency, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Ford Motor Co. retained its standing as the most efficient
among the three major auto makers, it said. Based on a 1996 survey
by a consulting group, however, Ford still lagged behind the North
American factories of Nissan Motor Co., Honda Motor Co. and Toyota
Motor Corp., the study said.
</P>
<P>
General Motors Corp., the largest among the three, improved its
production from better-engineered components requiring fewer parts
and less time to assemble.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler Corp. did the similar improvement in reducing the
number of parts required.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese auto makers -- which together now have about as
much North American production capacity as Ford does -- remain
substantially more efficient than their Big Three rivals,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Nissan's plant in Tennessee remained the most efficient among
the auto makers in North America. It required an average of just
28.3 hours of labor to produce a vehicle. Toyota required 29.5
hours, and Honda, 30.9. Meanwhile, Ford required 37.6 hours,
Chrysler 40.5 hours, and GM 44.6 hours, the report found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
