<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homeless Kinds Sleep in New York City Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 12 (xinhua) -- More and more homeless children
sleep in the New York City offices, psychiatric hospitals and
private home because of the child welfare system is virtually
filled to capacity.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the New York Times today, the number
of children pouring into foster care has surged for the first time
since 1989, leaping by 2,535, or 30 percent, over the last year.
Foster officials described the beds shortage as the worst since
late 1980's.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the rapid rise in the number of children
pouring into foster care to two reasons. One is the City
government's decision to absorb state cuts by slashing payments to
foster care agencies, the other is the City's implementation of
its policy of removing young people more quickly from abusive and
neglectful homes.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more and more children squeezed into a system with
fewer and fewer beds.
</P>
<P>
Over the last six months, more than 1,000 foster children, most
of them teeen-agers, have spent at least one night huddled on the
floor of the city's placement offices, child welfare statistics
show. More than 60 children now languish in psychiatric wards for
weeks or longer, while an uncounted number struggle to get by with
families unable to meet their special needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
