<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Approval of China's MFN Renewal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday urged Congressional leaders to approve the renewal of
China's most-favored-nation (MFN) trading status, warning that
denying China the status would hurt Hong Kong's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to House Speaker Newt Gingrich and minority leader
Dick Gephardt, Clinton said: "Reversing our course on trade with
China would rebound to the detriment of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Half of the U.S-China trade flowed through Hong Kong, Clinton
said. So revocation of China's MFN trading status would halve Hong
Kong's economic growth, double its unemployment with the loss of
85,000 jobs and reduce its trade by 32 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The White House also released a letter from all former
secretaries of state expressing their support for renewing the MFN
status for China.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that revoking China's MFN status "would
effectively cut off trade between our two countries and thereby
deal a devastating blow to our overall relationship".
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, Defense Secretary William Cohen told a
conference of the Asia Society that denying China the MFN status
would not only hurt U.S. economic interests, but also damage
U.S. strategic influence and interests in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Our friends and allies throughout Asia would question our
ability to carry out a coherent policy toward China, and thus
toward the region as a whole," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
