<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Agencies Urged to Adopt "Pro-Poor" Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Globalization needs more
management -- to open opportunities for the poorest countries, not
close or restrict them in order to create employment and avoid
greater economic disparities -- both among and within countries,
according to a UN report.
</P>
<P>
Richard Jolly, special adviser to United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and principal coordinator of the report, noted that
all countries and all major financial international agencies must
do more than just stand cheering on the sidelines about the
virtues of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The Human Development Report 1997 commissioned by UNDP said
that the global expansion of the trade and investment is
proceeding at breakneck speed -- but largely for the benefit of
the more dynamic and powerful countries in the North and South.
</P>
<P>
The just-released report points out that unless globalization
is carefully managed, poor countries and poor people will become
increasingly marginalized.
</P>
<P>
Already, annual losses to developing countries from unequal
access to trade, labor and finance have been estimated at 500
billion dollars, 10 times what they receive in foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Though the ratio of trade to gross domestic product (GDP) for
the world has been rising over the past decade, the least
developed countries, with 10 percent of the world's people, have
only 0.3 percent of the world trade -- half their share of two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The share of the poorest 20 percent of the world's population
has shrunk from 2.3 percent of world income in 1960 to 1.1 percent
today -- and it is still falling.
</P>
<P>
The report offers six policies that can help governments
minimize the damage of globalization and maximize the
opportunities:
</P>
<P>
-- manage trade and capital flows more carefully. A selective
approach to the global market would follow the example of most
East Asian countries, which have some import protection, some
industrial intervention and some limit on foreign direct
investment;
</P>
<P>
-- invest in poor people, including better education and more
training programs;
</P>
<P>
-- stimulate exports from small enterprises;
</P>
<P>
-- manage new technology with investment in appropriate
technology accompanied by strong policies to build up human
capital and foster small enterprises;
</P>
<P>
-- adopt policies of poverty reduction and building up safe
nets to mitigate income inequality and economic upheaval; and
</P>
<P>
-- improve governance to build up a stronger state to suppress
social chaos and organized crime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
