<HEADLINE> Egypt to Attend Islamic Summit in Ankara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri will go to Ankara Saturday to represent his country at
the first summit of the eight-member Islamic Group slated for
Sunday, the Egyptian MENA new agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The eight most populous Muslim countries, namely
Egypt, Turkey, Pakistan, Iran, Nigeria, Bangladesh, Malaysia and
Indonesia, are expected to sign a declaration launching the
Developing-8 (D-8) economic group.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri will attend the summit on behalf of President Hosni
Mubarak, who has apologized for not attending.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa will head Egypt's team to attend
the foreign ministerial meetings Saturday to prepare for the
summit.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, experts from the group met here to discuss joint
trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said after the meeting that the June 15 summit is still
in its early stages and the prospects for economic cooperation is
yet to be seen.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision taken by the foreign ministers of the
group during their first meeting in Istanbul, each member state
will be responsible for a certain field of cooperation. Egypt was
put in charge of the trade and cotton industry sectors.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Turkish Minister of State for Foreign
Affairs Abdullah Gul held important talks with Mubarak here
Wednesday on the Turkish military incursion into northern Iraq, an
issue that has prompted Egyptian and Arab condemnation.
</P>
<P>
Gul delivered a message from Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
to Mubarak defending the military operation.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said in the message that Turkey respects Iraq's
territorial integrity but he declined to fix a date for its troop
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak sent a message to Demirel last week in which he
expressed the Arab world's concern at the Turkish military
operation in northern Iraq that began on May 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
