<HEADLINE> Iran Heavily Subsidizes Bread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran will advance subsidies worth
1.67 billion U.S. dollars in the bread, the staple food for the
country's 62 million population in the Persian diet, this year.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Karimi Nouri, director general of Iran's Crop
Organization (ICO), was quoted by today's Persian daily Hamshahri
as saying that the subsidies are meant to alleviate economic
hardship for local citizens.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said, subsidies will be given directly to
the people to prevent the wasting of bread and the illegal sale of
subsidized wheat flour.
</P>
<P>
Nouri said that Iran consumes 10 million tonnes of wheat
annually, half of which is imported.
</P>
<P>
Bread riots used to be the source of social unrest before the
1979 Islamic revolution. The government now considers wheat a
strategic product, and encourages farmers to grow wheat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
