<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Reduction Has a Long Way to Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Much of the world's
population has benefited from economic advances in the past three
decades but extreme poverty can be eradicated only after multiple
strategies are adopted, according to a newly released UN agency's
report.
</P>
<P>
The Human Development Report 1997, commissioned by the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP), said that the strategies are
needed to: accelerate economic growth in the 100 countries caught
in stagnation or decline; implement policies that are "pro-poor"
or targeted at poverty reduction; and reverse the menacing
setbacks that create and recreate poverty, including HIV/AIDS,
violent conflict and environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
The report, the eighth in a series of annual reports
commissioned by UNDP, noted that for the developing countries the
gains in human and economic development have covered as much
distance in the past 30 years as the industrialized world did in a
century.
</P>
<P>
The achievements include: more than three-fourths of the
population can expect to survive to age 40; adult illiteracy has
been reduced by nearly half; and infant mortality has been cut
nearly three-fifths.
</P>
<P>
However, the other aspect of the reality is still alarming:
nearly a third of the developing world's population -- about 1.3
billion people -- live on less than one US dollar a day; more than
800 million people do not get enough to eat; nor has the progress
been equally distributed.
</P>
<P>
While recognizing that each nation will need to adopt is own
prescription for reducing poverty, the report identifies six
priorities for action:
</P>
<P>
-- initiate people-centered policies that give individuals,
households and communities expanded access to economic, social,
political, environmental and personal assets;
</P>
<P>
-- work toward gender equality, both as an end and as a means
to eradication of poverty;
</P>
<P>
-- focus on pro-poor growth in the 100 or so countries from the
developing world with a minimum target of three percent per capita
income growth per year;
</P>
<P>
-- improve the management of globalization, including better
trade policies, fair rules and fair terms for poor countries to
enter markets;
</P>
<P>
-- create a political environment so that poor people and poor
communities can be heard rather than suppressed and oppressed; and
</P>
<P>
-- take special actions for special situations to prevent
economic reversal, including peace-building efforts in war-torn
countries, providing more support to reduce their debt, increase
their share of aid and enhance their entry into global market,
especially for Africa's agricultural exports.
</P>
<P>
UNDP estimated that in the next decade the additional cost of
achieving basic social services for all and to help the poor to
get rid of poverty will amount to 80 billion dollars a year, only
0.32 percent of the world income of 25 trillion dollars or less
than the combined net worth of the seven richest men in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The resources needed to implement this agenda are a mere
fraction of the resources available -- globally and in most
countries," said Richard Jolly, special advisor to the UNDP and
principal coordinator of the report.
</P>
<P>
UNDP Administrator James Gustave Speth said that the report's
most important message is that poverty is no longer inevitable.
The world has the material and natural resources, the know-how and
the people to make a poverty-free world a reality in less than a
generation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
