<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Breaks Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- There are reports of heavy
fighting between the forces from the Ethiopian government and
militiamen loyal to the Islamic fundamentalist group of Al-Itihad
Al-Islam along the border region of Gedo this morning.
</P>
<P>
Early reports said the Ethiopian forces using more than 25
tanks and armored vehicles in support with quite a large number
of infantry troops have captured the towns of Luq and Bulo Hawo.
The forces of invasion have also captured dozens of villages
including Malkaharrey, Bohol Garas, Dhusay and Karaban.
</P>
<P>
According to the report the fighting has started early in the
morning at Karaban village 25 km west of Luq town, the main
headquarters of Al-Itihad. The report further more said the line
of the fighting has today been the largest covering more than 70
km terrain.
</P>
<P>
All VHF field and commercial radios in the important towns of
Bulo Hawo and Luq went out of the air just before mid day local
time. However a radio owner who escaped the town of Bulo Hawo
said he could see a cloud of smoke atop the town.
</P>
<P>
Since the invasion has been quick and not anticipated, most of
the inhabitants of those towns have been inside their places when
the Ethiopians have captured their towns. Few of the young men
and the armed militiamen of Al-Itihad have hardly run out of the
towns to escape possible killing and torture.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Al-Itihad Al-Islam here in Mogadishu, Mr Ahmed
Bile Hassan said he can not give out the casualty figures, but
admitted the fall of the two towns to the Ethiopians. Mr Hassan
said their forces have showed resistance to the forces of
occupation, but later on retreated out of their headquarters town
for what he called military tactic.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the renewed Ethiopian advance into Somalia's
territory is not yet known, however, the spokesman for Al-Itihad
claimed that the aim of the Ethiopians is to capture the port
town of Kismaio in their attempt to obtain a seaport for their
country after loosing Assab of Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the fighting still continues at this moment at
the outskirts of Luq town with the Ethiopian forces still chasing
out the militiamen of Al-Itihad Al-Islam. The fighting is
reported to be the most serious, however no casualty figures are
available from either side.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian forces have earlier been controlling the border
town of Dolow-Somalia since December last year. The Ethiopian
incursion into Somalia followed Ethiopia's claim of chasing out
Muslim fundamentalists based in Gedo region of southern Somalia.
The invasion on the pretext of fighting an Islamic organization
has been criticized by most of the Somali politicians.
</P>
<P>
This fighting today is taking place at a time when more than
20 Somali factions are flying into Addis Ababa for what is called
a reconciliatory conference in an effort to end up the long
standing political crises in Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
