<HEADLINE> Telecom Services in Zambia to be Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Telecommunications Company
(ZAMTEL) is to set up new digital microwave links between Lusaka
and the industrial Copperbelt province at the cost of 4.5 million
US dollars to replace the analogue microwave that is currently
used.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by ZAMTEL Director for public relations
Bernard Sakala in an interview in Kitwe, Times of Zambia reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The move will pave the way for ZAMTEL to introduce GSM digital
cellular telephones which the company intends to introduce on the
market soon.
</P>
<P>
Sakala said, "Previously ZAMTEL could not introduce the GSM
digital cellular telephones on the market because the company was
still using analogue microwave links."
</P>
<P>
with the new investment in place, ZAMTEL will be able to
introduce the GSM cellular telephones that are widely used in
most parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
ZAMTEL has an ongoing program to replace old equipment with
modern ones and this is part of the project. The analogue system
to be replaced will be used in other parts of the country such as
rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
