<HEADLINE> Zambian Official Calls for Protection of Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Director of fisheries Gordon
Mudenda has called on chiefs along lake Bangweulu in Samfya to
persuade their subjects to stop immediately using bad fishing
methods.
</P>
<P>
He told 10 chiefs at a workshop on fishing held in Samfya that
the bad methods have led to a reduction of the fish population in
the lake Bangweulu, the largest lake in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to a research, Zambians consume 70,000 tons of fish
of which 15,000 is caught from lake Bangweulu.
</P>
<P>
"The number has greatly dropped from the 1960s because of bad
fishing methods used by fishermen," Mudenda said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the chiefs to educate the fishermen to consider
future generations who would benefit from the fish there.
</P>
<P>
It is important for the chiefs to work hand in hand with the
fisheries department since the department has limited wildlife
officers to monitor had fishing methods, the director said.
</P>
</TEXT>
