<HEADLINE> France Sees Wider Threat in Congo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- France considers the on-going
fighting in the Congo Republic a threat to the whole region of
central and western Africa.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux said: "France
expresses its deep worry over the gravity of the situation in
Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
"It strongly condemns the fighting which has already resulted
in numerous victims in the civilian population of Congo, the
destruction of the country and which could make up a threat for
the peace of the whole region."
</P>
<P>
He called on the two warring sides of the Congo Republic to
start a lasting ceasefire and join negotiations mediated by the
mayor of Brazzaville, Bernard Kolelas, and Gabonese President Omar
Bongo, in order to restore "civil peace" which was indispensable
for the holding of the country's presidential election on July 27.
</P>
<P>
Though some Frenchmen repatriated from Congo have complained
about the incapability of the French services in helping them, the
spokesman praised the French troops, the French embassy and
consulates in Congo.
</P>
<P>
They were operating "beyond the possible" to help evacuate
thousands of French nationals and other foreigners from
Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
About 1,200 French troops, backed by tanks and armored
vehicles, are stationed in Brazzaville to escort foreigners to
safe areas, and to keep open the Brazzaville international airport
to evacuate them on military aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
