<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crown Prince: Jordan Concerned With Turkey's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan Ibn
Talal said here today that Jordan is concerned about Turkey's
cross-border military operations which are going on in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Hassan made the remarks upon his arrival at the Ankara airport
for a one-day working visit to Turkey to present the views of King
Hussein of Jordan to Turkish President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
The crown prince said that "Jordan always condemns all kinds of
terrorism. We know that the (military) operations are staged
against terrorism. But, we can not accept any change which will
take place in the map of the region."
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government supports a solution to the problems
through dialogue, said Hassan, adding that the stance of Jordan on
this issue will be a subject during his talks with Demirel and
Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000-strong Turkish government troops launched a
massive cross-border military campaign on May 14 to attack the
illegal Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in northern Iraq, drawing
severe criticism from many regional countries.
</P>
<P>
More than 23,000 people, including PKK members, civilians and
government troops, have been killed in conflicts since August
1984 when the PKK started a separatist war for an independent
Kurdish state in eastern and southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
