<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Diplomats and United Nations officials were less than
enthusiastic about the strings attached to a deal worked out by
the Clinton Administration and the Senate that would allow
repayment of a large part of the American debt to the
organization. Several envoys said that not all the demands made by
Senators would be accepted by all 184 member countries.
</P>
<P>
-- Republicans in Congress moved to prevent tens of thousands
of Welfare recipients from being covered by the minimum wage. They
want to overturn a recent ruling by President Clinton that
guarantees the minimum wage for welfare recipients participating
in "workfare" programs run by public agencies or non-profit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- At odds with congressional Republicans on the best approach
for fighting juvenile crime, President Clinton said yesterday he
is using his executive power to create rules designed to prevent
guns from falling into the possession of minors.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- A house panel decided this week to cut the Pentagon's
fiscal '98 purchase of a new version of the F-18 to four from 20,
and use the 2.1 billion dollars saved to buy old, cheaper versions
of the fighter. The move, while unlikely to stand, explicitly
rejects the strategy Defense Secretary Cohen had chosen.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton administration will nominate NACCP Legal Defense
Fund Lawyer Bill Lann Lee to head the Justice Department's civil
rights division. 
</P>
