<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Punishes Stock Market Rule Violators (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A number of financial institutions
and people that violated securities market rules, including the
Shenzhen Development Bank and its president, have been severely
punished, according to an official decision, which was made public
here today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after thorough investigations by the
Securities Committee of the State Council, the People's Bank of
China, the State Auditing Administration, the China Securities
Regulatory Commission and other relevant government departments.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Development Bank used a total of 311 million yuan
to speculate in its own stocks between March 1996 and April this
year, illegally making 90.34 million yuan in profit, the decision
said.
</P>
<P>
"This act has violated the regulations of the Commercial Bank
Law banning commercial banks from engaging in stock business and
violated State rules prohibiting listed companies from trading in
stocks of their own companies," it said.
</P>
<P>
What's more serious is that the Shenzhen Development Bank
continued to speculate in its own stocks until April this year,
which has gravely disturbed the normal market order and misled
investors, the decision said.
</P>
<P>
It said that relevant departments have decided to discharge He
Yun from his post as President of the Shenzhen Development Bank
and deny his access to the financial and securities market for
five years.
</P>
<P>
Li Wei, who was in charge of securities operations of the
Shenzhen Development Bank, was also disciplined, according to the
decision.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Development Bank has been fined and its illegal
profits confiscated. It has also been ordered to sell its holdings
of its own stocks and turn all profits over to the State coffer.
</P>
<P>
The decision said that between September and December of 1996,
the Shanghai branch of the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China
(ICBC) provided lendings and overdrafts in huge amounts to some
securities companies for stock speculation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Punishes Stock Market Rule Violators (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the period, ICBC Shanghai lent 910 million to Haitong
Securities Company and 6.31 billion yuan to Shenyin &AMP; Wanguo
Securities Company. It also provided Haitong with overdrafts
averaging 1.2 billion yuan daily in late October and one billion
yuan in November. Its overdrafts to Shenyin &AMP; Wanguo averaged 580
million yuan in September, 830 million yuan in October and 910
million yuan in November.
</P>
<P>
ICBC Shanghai continued to provide credit overdrafts to certain
securities institutions after the publication of a commentary in
the People's Daily on December 16, 1996, with the amount reaching
395 million yuan on December 25 alone.
</P>
<P>
"The act of ICBC Shanghai has violated State regulations
banning all financial institutions from offering lendings or
providing overdrafts for stock trading, encouraged speculation at
the stock market and had a very bad impact on the standardized and
stable development of the stock market," the decision said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the relevant departments have decided to dismiss
Shen Ruolei from his post as president of ICBC Shanghai, the
decision said.
</P>
<P>
Guangshen (Guangzhou-Shenzhen) Railway Stock Co. Ltd. is a
company listed in Hong Kong. Without a decision by the board of
directors, Chairman of the board Ge Wen'an in December 1996
entrusted Jun'an International Finance Co. Ltd, which is not
qualified to raise funds inside the country, to carry out "capital
asset management" for 300 million yuan of the funds the company
raised through stock offerings, according to the decision.
</P>
<P>
The latter then transferred the funds to Jun'an Securities
Company for stock speculation and illegally made 40 million yuan
in profits.
</P>
<P>
"These acts have gravely violated relevant State regulations
and accounting rules on securities," the decision said.
</P>
<P>
The relevant departments will, through legal procedures,
dismiss Ge Wen'an as chairman of the board and Zeng Xianzhao as
the chief accountant, and will have their demerits recorded.
</P>
<P>
The company has also been ordered to withdraw the 300 million
yuan it has used in violation of rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Punishes Stock Market Rule Violators (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Investigations have also shown that since last September,
Haitong Securities Company, Shenyin &AMP; Wanguo Securities Company,
and Guangfa Securities Company have illegally obtained huge
amounts of bank funds. Through continual buying and selling and a
great number of two-way offsets, they manipulated the stock prices
of Shanghai Petroleum, Lujiazui, Nanyou Industry and other
companies, which resulted in abnormal fluctuations in the prices
of these stocks, disturbed the normal order of the stock market,
harmed the interests of other investors, and boosted
over-speculation at the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The relevant departments have decided to discharge Li Huizhen
as board chairman and general manager of Haitong Securities
Company, Kan Zhidong as chairman of Shenyin &AMP; Wanguo Securities
Company, and Ma Qingquan as general manager of Guangfa Securities
Company. Their demerits have also been recorded.
</P>
<P>
These three companies have been fined and their business of
trading in stocks has been suspended for one year.
</P>
<P>
Because of rule violations, Jun'an Securities Company has also
been barred from trading in stocks for half a year and has its
illegal incomes confiscated.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the State financial and securities
regulatory departments have decided to further beef up law
enforcement in order to deal a blow to all sorts of law and rule
violations at the financial and securities markets.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials of the state-owned banks that provide other
institutions or individuals with funds for stock speculation and
the listed companies, securities firms and institutional investors
that speculate in stocks with bank credits, together with market
manipulators, will be dismissed and denied market access, the
decision said.
</P>
<P>
Those whose wrongdoings are illegal will be brought to justice,
the decision noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
