<HEADLINE> Moi: Africa Faces Marginalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
had cautioned that Africa faced marginalization as Africans were
moving in the wrong direction and disadvantaged in the
globalization of trade.
</P>
<P>
Moi was quoted as saying on Wednesday at a workshop of the
stakeholders in the small-scale enterprises that nearly the whole
of Africans spent most of their time on empty politicking.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Africans were waging wars against themselves as
if destined for total destruction, adding that they were
completely oblivious of development and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
Like the rhino and elephant, the president said, the Africans
are an endangered species owing to their drive for
self-destruction, Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the mighty Group of Seven were the ones
who dictated the world's economic order, adding that developing
countries were disadvantaged in the globalization of trade as
they had to compete with the technological giants of the West.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the days of Alexander the Great, Moi said, some
nations have never conquered their instinctive desire to colonize
others.
</P>
<P>
"There was Alexander the Great who wept for lack of more space
to colonize. Then came the Roman Empire, followed by the
Ottomans and later the British Empire, and now America is a
superpower," the Kenyan Head of State said,
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that no foreigners would help Africans develop
and the development of the region would depend on the people
themselves and on the effectiveness of the local economic blocs
like the East African Co-operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
