<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Philippine Ruling Party Facing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- With the merger of three major
Philippine opposition parties Wednesday, the country's ruling
Lakas-NUCD party will face a stronger-than-ever opposition in the
May 1998 general elections.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the country's largest opposition party, Laban Ng
Demokratikong Pilipino (LDP), and two other opposition groups --
the Nationalist People's Party (NPC) and the Patrido ng Masang
Pilipino (PMP), signed an agreement to formally merge their forces
in order to win the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that a stronger-than-ever
opposition party emerging from the merger will become a major
obstacle for the Lakas-NUCD party led by President Fidel Ramos to
continue its one-party rule in 1998.
</P>
<P>
They said the merger enabled the previously-fractional
opposition to have better chances to beat the governing party,
which itself is in danger of breakup as its presidential aspirants
are competing for the anointment of President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Under the merger agreement, the three opposition parties will
be dissolved to form a new opposition party called Laban Ng
Makabayang Masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Common Filipinos).
</P>
<P>
The leader of the three parties agreed to choose a common
presidential standard bearer for the new party to compete with the
presidential candidate put up by the ruling party in the 1998
polls.
</P>
<P>
Controlling 14 of the 24 seats in the Senate, the new party
enjoys a comfortable majority in the upper house. In the
204-member House of Representatives, the new party holds 49 seats,
compared to 112 held by Lakas-NUCD members.
</P>
<P>
The party also has the support of 35 provincial governors and
vice governors and 500 other government officials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, analysts here said the final ruling given Tuesday by
the Supreme Court on the fate of charter change move also gave the
new unified opposition party a good opportunity to contend with
the ruling party in the general elections.
</P>
<P>
The ruling upheld the court's earlier decision prohibiting a
pro-Ramos group from proceeding its bid to change the constitution
to lift the term limit of Ramos, effectively dashing any hope for
Ramos of running for a second term.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's 1987 constitution, Ramos should step down
as his six-year single term expires in June 1998. But Ramos, whose
economic reforms revitalized the staggering economy, is widely
seen to gain a runaway re-election victory if being allowed to
serve a second term.
</P>
<P>
"With the unbeatable Ramos not available for re-election,
opposition presidential candidates will have greater chances in
winning the election," said Senator Juan Flavier.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the ruling party is facing the danger of
breakup as its presidential aspirants will intensify their efforts
to get the endorsement of Ramos, equal to 4 million votes, after
the Supreme Court handed down the final ruling.
</P>
<P>
"The ruling party is facing higher risk of breakup than the
united opposition," said Senate President and NPC chief Ernesto
Maceda.
</P>
<P>
But meanwhile, analysts said the new opposition party still
falls short of being a formidable challenge to the ruling party
for the moment since it fails to include two other opposition
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
They said the new party should win over the Kabalikat ng
Malayang Pilipino party and the People's Reform Party in order to
expand the united opposition front.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
