<HEADLINE> Profile: Chan, Recommended as HK High Court Chief Judge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Justice Patrick Chan was
recommended here today as chief judge of Hong Kong's High Court
after July 1, but the recommendation still needs support from the
Provisional Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the recommendation from the Judicial Officers
Recommendation Commission (Designate) of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa said:
"Chan will play a key role in the HKSAR judiciary after its
establishment."
</P>
<P>
"Chan is highly respected by members of the Judiciary and the
profession for his personal and judicial qualities," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Chan, born in Hong Kong on October 21, 1948, was educated in
Hong Kong at Wah Yan College. He graduated from the University of
Hong Kong with a Bachelor of Law decree in 1974 and a
Post-graduate Certificate in Law in 1975.
</P>
<P>
He was called to the Hong Kong Bar in 1976 and was in private
practice until his appointment as a District Judge in November
1987. He was appointed Deputy Registrar at the Supreme Court in
November 1991 and a High Court Judge in May 1992.
</P>
<P>
Chan is the chairman respectively of the Steering Committee on
the Use of Chinese in Courts, the Joint Examination Board on
P.C.LL and the Release Under Supervision Board.
</P>
<P>
Active in social services, he is chairman of the Social Studies
Advisory Committee of the Hong Kong Polytechnic University, patron
of the Hong Kong Social Workers Association, vice chairman of the
Christian Family Service Center, and a member of Social Work
Committee of Caritas Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Chan, also an honorary lecturer of the Chinese University of
Hong Kong, is married.  
</P>
</TEXT>
