<HEADLINE> Thyssen Plans Takeover of U.S. Work Tools Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The German industrial firm Thyssen
said today it is planning to take over the United States' largest
work tools and machinery maker, Giddings and Lewis (G&AMP;L), within
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Thyssen, which intends to integrate G&AMP;L into its Essen-based
subsidiary Thyssen Industrie, said it would offer up to 700
million U.S. dollars in cash, or 21 dollars per share for the deal
via its subsidiary Thyssen Holding Corp.
</P>
<P>
Thyssen said the G&AMP;L management would advise shareholders to
accept the offer. It said managements of both firms agreed that
the a merger would provide "outstanding potential for considerable
synergy effects."
</P>
<P>
The American company has eight factories in the United States,
one in Canada and one in Germany, with annual sales of 700 million
U.S. dollars. About half of its business is in the automobile
industry.
</P>
<P>
The takeover of G&AMP;L will double the revenues of Thyssen's
production sector to some 2.4 billion marks (1.4 billion U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
