<HEADLINE> Kim Young-sam Questioned on Election Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korean opposition lawmakers
put an open questionnaire to President Kim Young-sam today, asking
him to disclose the truth on the controversial campaign fund in
the 1992 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The seven-point open questionnaire, submitted by 124 opposition
lawmakers from the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and
the United Liberal Democrats (ULD), launched a new round of attack
on the president and the ruling New Korea Party (NKP) before the
coming presidential election in December.
</P>
<P>
In a public address two weeks ago, Kim admitted that he spent
in excess of the legal ceiling in the 1992 election, but refused
to reveal the amounts, saying no records were available five years
after the election.
</P>
<P>
In today's questionnaire, the opposition turned the target to
the sources of the funds as well as the expenditures, directly
asking the president to reveal the amount of funds he received
from businesses and citizens in the 1992 election which he can
still recall, even though he has little information on the funds.
</P>
<P>
They also asked whether Kim had received political funds from
former President Roh Tae-woo and the Hanbo Business Group before
and during the 1992 election, whether he had received any
congratulatory money after he won the election and whether he had
received a report on the management of the leftover campaign funds
which his son Kim Hyun-chul took over.
</P>
<P>
The opposition lawmakers said that any money received
indirectly by the president through his son and his close aide
would be viewed as a direct receipt of funds.
</P>
<P>
Kim was also asked whether he really wants to reform the
current high-cost election system by mentioning the "political
reforms and the grave decision" in the address to the nation two
weeks ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
