<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000 Year Old Tomb Unearthed in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A 2,000-year old tomb dating
back to the Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- A.D. 24) has been
unearthed in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
A local archaeologist said that the 12.5-meter long burial
chamber was lined with wood, and this was the first time that such
material was discovered lining one of the area's tombs.
</P>
<P>
Some 430 funerary objects ranging from lacquer ware, wooden and
bamboo articles to pottery, jade ware, and iron ware have also
been found, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, thousands of fruit seeds and crops samples
have been well preserved in the tomb thanks to the grave builders'
skill in sealing up the structure to prevent the infiltration of
water.
</P>
<P>
Characters found on some of the funerary articles are of high
value to archeologists engaged in research on ancient
calligraphy. He added that many wooden models of daily-life
instruments were also unearthed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
