<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Announces New Measures to Woo HK Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Macao enacted a set of new
regulations today to woo retired Hong Kong residents to invest in
Macao.
</P>
<P>
Retired Hong Kong residents or veterans will be allowed to live
in Macao for up to three years or more provided they make
investment of no less than 500,000 patacas (about 63,290
U.S. dollars) worth in the territory buying properties.
</P>
<P>
That amount of investment was only half of the previous
requirement. The government cut the investment demand from two
million patacas to one million in April last year.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest government gazette, the newly-revised
edition of residency regulations says that a person who is viewed
as a major investor of no less than 500,000 patacas and his or her
family members are entitled to acquire an 18-month temporary
residence permit, which is also renewable if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Major investors themselves, specialized technical professionals
and their family members are entitled to acquire a three-year
permit, which is also renewable.
</P>
<P>
But the gazette says that beneficiaries of the new regulations
are restricted only to permanent Hong Kong residents, retired
professionals or veterans, who can economically support
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The move was applauded by local businessmen as a boost to
Macao's sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
"It is a spring season coming late," said Chui Sai Cheong,
president of the Macao Society of Economics Study. "The policy to
attract investment will benefit the property market and bring a
boom to the consumption market."
</P>
<P>
An analysis in today's Macao Daily News, however, is cautious
about the effect of the new regulations. It says the fact that
people outside Macao are reluctant to move into Macao is not
because they do not have enough money, but because the government
has to improve its working efficiency in handling applications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
