<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mud Chinese Map Made </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A man in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province has made a Chinese map made of soil from 31
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions of the country in
order to express his excitement over the return of Hong Kong to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Niu Shigang, from Harbin, capital city of Heilongjiang, toured
around the country to gather soil samples for more than four
months. In Beijing, he collected soil from the Old Summer Palace
which was burned down by the British and French joint forces in
1860. In Sichuan Province he took soil from Guang'an, hometown of
late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
"The places from which I collected soil from are the most
sensitive to the memories of the nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Once back home in Harbin, he placed his soil samples in
31 glass structures in the form of outlines of the provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions. The colorful map weighs
nearly 100 kilos.
</P>
<P>
The man said that the map is not yet complete, "with places for
Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan still vacant."
</P>
<P>
He hopes that some Hong Kong people can help him fill in the
Hong Kong area gap with Hong Kong's soil on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the map hangs at the entrance of the Zhaolin Park in
Harbin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
