<HEADLINE> HK Students Sent to Work-study Program in Chinese Inland Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will send its largest
contingent of tertiary students to a work-study program in the
Chinese inland areas, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
About 200 students and graduates from the Chinese University of
Hong Kong have been awarded training placements or study trips to
the Chinese inland areas as part of the China Career Development
Program.
</P>
<P>
Vice Chancellor Arthur Li Lwok-cheung said the program was
launched to promote academic links with Chinese universities and
to cater for future market needs.
</P>
<P>
About half of the participants, selected from more than 300
candidates with knowledge of Putonghua, will visit renowned
Beijing University and Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
The four-week course includes visit to public institutions in
Beijing and talks by Chinese officials and academics on
socio-political and economic systems of the Chinese inland areas.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the first-hand experience I get in Beijing will help me
prepare for my future career, especially if I'm offered a job
there," said Connie Tang Pek-man, a business administration
student.
</P>
<P>
The internship part of the program is a six-week placement at a
branch office of a Hong Kong company or cultural organization in
Guangzhou, Shenzhen or Beijing.  
</P>
