<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annual MFN Debate Hindering Sino-US Trade Growth: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The US Congress' annual debate on
whether to grant China the most favored nation status (MFN) goes
against the need for trade and economic cooperation between the
two countries, Foreign Ministry spokesman Cui Tiankai said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Cui said that the annual debate also hinders the further
expansion of bilateral trade and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that China believes that the ongoing
debate about China's MFN status in the US is unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the two sides are well aware that retaining
the MFN status for China will bring a lot of benefits to both
countries. If the MFN status were revoked, both countries will
have their interests damaged, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that bringing a stable, long-term bilateral
relationship into the 21st century is a prominent responsibility
of the two big nations for the Asia-Pacific region and the world
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Trade and economic relations constitute an important component
of the Sino-US relationship, he said, adding that bilateral trade
and economic cooperation should be normal, reciprocal and mutually
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that it is hard to comprehend the motive of
some US people insisting on carrying out the annual debate about
the MFN issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite continued growth of US exports to China
and rapid expansion of bilateral trade in recent years, the US
restriction on the export hi-tech products to China has become a
major reason for its trade deficit with China. The restriction has
posed many obstacles to the expansion of US exports to China, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side hopes that the US side will take measures to
reduce obstacles in bilateral trade and economic cooperation, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
