<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Sinks on Rate Cut Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar sank to its
lowest level in four months today as new job data was interpreted
as strongly supporting the prospects of another cut in official
interest rates in the near term.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 75.18 US cents, off a post-data
low of 75.03. It had closed previously at 75.98 US cents.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia foreign exchange trader Paul Macarounas
said the unit had been trading quietly ahead of the jobs report at
around 75.65 US cents.
</P>
<P>
"And then there was no hesitation from the market to sell it,"
he said, noting the break of key support at 75.50 US cents.
</P>
<P>
The May labor force report showed total employment fell by a
seasonally adjusted 40,300 to 8.38 million in the month, compared
to a rise of 37,000 in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate rose to 8.8 percent from 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 22 economists conducted today by the Australian
Associated Press found that 41 percent thought there was now a
better than 50 percent chance of a rate cut occurring in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Australian dollar regained some ground against
the Japanese yen on the day, in line with a bounce higher in the
US dollar/yen rate.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 85.69 yen, up from 84.23 Wednesday
and ended at 1.2944 marks, from 1.3012 Wednesday. 
</P>
