<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close At Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares raced to a
record closing high today, inspired by dramatic surge in News Corp
and renewed speculation of another easing in monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 24.4 points up at 2,638.1, off
a fresh intraday peak of 2,646.4.
</P>
<P>
The close beat the previous record of 2,628.9 points reached on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lance Jones' broker Hamish Dee said the market rallied on a
combination of strong performances from News Corp and ANZ bank,
and weaker-than-expected employment figures which revived talks of
an interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
"News Corp was the big mover along with ANZ, so those two
stocks between them were the main reason for our market closing up
as strongly as it did," Dee said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics released the labor force
data, showing the country's unemployment rate was a seasonally
adjusted 8.8 percent in May after being 8.7 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Economists had been expecting a jobless rate at 8.7 percent and
the creation of about 15,600 jobs during the month.
</P>
<P>
The fall prompted economists to increase their expectations for
the Reserve Bank of Australia to ease rates further in the second
half of 1997, to encourage economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp announced back-to-back merger and
expansion deals worth 2.8 billion US dollars which will give the
media group a way into the highly competitive US cable market.
</P>
<P>
The company will merge a subsidiary of its Fox Kids Worldwide
Inc with International Family Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
News Corp's ordinary shares closed 40 cents firmer at 6.27
Australian dollars on turnover of 9.5 million shares while its
preferred shares jumped 42 cents to 5.23 Australian dollars on
turnover of 6.91 million.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was 48.1 points higher at 4,138.0,
while the all resources gained 4.6 to close at 1,483.2.
</P>
<P>
The banking index lifted 71.2 points to 4,701.5, spurred by
sharp rises in potential takeover target ANZ.
</P>
<P>
A broker said ANZ was "the favorite bank" to be taken over by a
foreign institution.
</P>
<P>
The resource sector was led by Rio Tinto, which gained 46 cents
to 21.98 Australian dollars, while WMC Ltd added 12 cents to 8.22
Australian dollars and mining giant BHP finished four cents higher
at 18.70 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 8.3 points softer to 1,544.7 while in
Sydney spot gold closed at 342.35 US dollars per fine ounce
compared with Wednesday's close of 343.45 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 411.72 million shares, valued at
977.22 million Australian dollars (742.68 million US dollars),
with falls outnumbering rises 574 to 556.  
</P>
</TEXT>
