<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet to Offer S. Africans Cheaper Phone Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africans will enjoy
much cheaper international telephone calls when the Global
Internetwork service is introduced in South Africa next month,
the local daily "Business Day" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The launch of Internet service will see the price of
international calls fall 80 percent in some cases to equal the
cost of local calls, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The two-way system, which is capable of transmitting voice,
fax, video and data via the Internet, would not require the
caller or recipient to have a computer, Ivan Fafandjel, the local
presentative of call-back operator U.S.A. Global Link was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The system transforms analogue voice tones to digital signal
for transmission over the Internet. The digital signal is
reconverted to analogue for transmission over the local telephone
service.
</P>
<P>
Fafandjel said the discounted call rate is expected to attract
strong support from local private and business users.
</P>
<P>
However, the plan has been slammed by South Africa's
state-owned telephone company, Telkom, which stands to lose
valuable long-distance call revenue.
</P>
<P>
Rhynie Greef, the managing executive of Telkom's international
business unit, said the use of the Internet for voice
communications was in direct conflict with Telkom's exclusive
rights to provide fixed-line voice communication services.
</P>
<P>
He referred to operators that used the system as "pirates",
taking what was not theirs and investing nothing in the
establishment or maintenance of the local telecommunications net
work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
