<HEADLINE> NATO Defense Ministers to Meet on Command Structure, Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- NATO defence ministers gathered
here today for a two-day meeting to discuss reforms of NATO's
military command structure, peacekeeping mission in Bosnia and
NATO's eastwards expansion.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-France struggle for control of the Allied Forces
Southern Europe, NATO's joint command headquarters, in Italy's
Naples, will also be on the top of the meeting's agenda.
</P>
<P>
France has demanded that the post in the Southern Region, which
has so far been held by an American general, be handed over to an
European in order to make the European defence identity more
visible, while the United States has rejected the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will discuss a greater international role in
Bosnia, demanded by the United States, including sending a special
force to find and arrest indicted war criminals, though there are
talks of NATO cutting its 35,000 peace protection troops in Bosnia
to 20,000 by November.
</P>
<P>
They will exchange views on the countries to be invited to join
NATO during its summit in Madrid on July 8-9.
</P>
<P>
The United States has argued that only the Czech Republic,
Hungary and Poland are allowed to join NATO in the first wave,
while most of the European allies insist that Romania and Slovenia
be added to the wave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
