<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johannesburg Remains World's Low-Price City: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Johannesburg, the biggest
commercial city in South Africa, is among the least expensive
cities in the world, according to a latest survey released by the
Economist Intelligence Unit.
</P>
<P>
Average Johannesburg prices are 38 percent below those of New
York, the base city of the unit's index. Thus, while New York is
100 for comparative purposes, Johannesburg has 62 points.
</P>
<P>
Of all cities investigated, the cheapest city is Tripoli, with
average prices two thirds below New Yorks, followed by Bombay,
New Delhi, Tehran, Karachi and Harare.
</P>
<P>
The most expensive in the world, with a cost of living 54
percent higher than New York, is Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Oslo, Moscow, Hong Kong, Libreville, Paris, Zurich and Geneva
are among the top 10 most costly cities. London is 14th on the
list.
</P>
<P>
Following the strengthening of the U.S. Dollar, it is less
expensive to live in Frankfurt, Dublin, Madrid and Rome than in
New York, the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
