<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glamor of An Euro-Style Street Restored in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harbin, June 12 (Xinhua) -- People here compare it to London's
Regent Street, or even the Champs Elysees in Paris. It is
convincing when the century-old Central Street bears its refreshed
look, a result of 18-month repairing, painting and decorating.
</P>
<P>
The 1.5-km-long Central Street, with its exotic appearance fronted
by hundreds of European-style buildings, has become an outstanding
landmark of Harbin, capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
Its history dates back to 1890 when massive construction of
railway network in China's northeast drew flocks of migrants from
Russia, France, the United States, Germany, Britain and Italy to
the city. They resided along the street, and built buildings
characteristic of their homelands.
</P>
<P>
Within a decade or two, Central Street had became one of the
best-known and prosperous streets in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
However, in the past 100 years, its glamor gradually faded.
The look and interiors of many buildings along the street became
rundown and tarnished.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, the municipal government of Harbin
decided to refurbish the street and make it a shopping street. At
the same time the street became a traffic free zone.
</P>
<P>
Now the fruits of the work can be enjoyed. The street now bears
a bright appearance, mainly of yellow, white and green colors, only
occasionally a gray. As for the architectural styles, there are
examples of Baroque, Renaissance, Neo-Classicalism and even a bit
of avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
To Chinese people, the street is a gallery of European art
and architecture. Besides, Harbin wants it to be a tourist
attraction to foreign visitors who, while walking in and out
exquisite shops, may feel they are at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toilet Revolution Relieves Local Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan province is
spearheading a toilet revolution with real Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The "funnel-like toilet with double-urns" is the province's
special invention for farmers, who were used to relieving
themselves in shallow pits dug on farmland.
</P>
<P>
The new toilet is said to have more functions than the old one,
and benefits both farm production and the call of nature. Experts
said that it can effectively kill harmful bacteria while
preserving 95 percent of the effluent's nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
Waste recovered from the toilet can be used to fertilize the
fields -- and it's cleaner, making the spread of infectious
diseases less of a threat, experts said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the toilet is quite cheap, according to sources,
who said that the toilets are being used by 6.8 million farming
families in Henan.
</P>
<P>
Toilet revolutions are also being waged in cities, where the
main problem is the stench of old public lavatories in back
alleyways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
