<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Gets Closer to International Appraisal Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China's fledgling but
rapidly-developing asset appraisal industry is adopting
international standards rapidly, according to officials at a 3-day
international symposium which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
China has made giant strides in its effort to adopt
international appraisal standards since the industry was
established in 1989, an official of the State Administration of
State Property said.
</P>
<P>
The issuing and implementation of a set of regulations on the
evaluation of state assets in 1991 marked the first step, which
indicated that China's asset appraising industry had
embarked on a path of standardized development, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Other major steps include the founding of the China Asset
Evaluation Association in December 1993, the introduction of a
system of certified public valuers and the publication of
opinions and advice on practical asset evaluation.
</P>
<P>
As enterprises reform, transfer of property rights and asset
restructuring are on the increase, hence asset evaluation
has become important.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that China had more than 3,300 asset
evaluation agencies and over 50,000 professional appraisers by the
end of last year. Evaluators appraised assets worth more than
2,202 billion yuan (about 265.3 billion US dollars) in book value
between 1989 and last year, with the post-evaluation value of the
appraised assets reaching 3,241 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to existing Chinese laws and regulations, state
assets must be appraised for economic activities such as setting
up Sino-overseas equity joint ventures or contractual ventures,
asset auctions and transfers, enterprise mergers, bankruptcies and
alliances.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was jointly organized by the China Asset Evaluation
Association, United Nations Development Program and China
International Economic and Technical Exchange Center of the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
