<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Smoking Campaign Launched In Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A national anti-smoking campaign
designed to encourage smokers to kick the habit was launched today
by federal Health Minister Michael Wooldridge.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, which targets the 25 percent of Australians who
smoke, is the first to enjoy the support of federal, state and
territory governments, Wooldridge said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to him, 18,000 Australians died each year from
smoking-related illness, while treatment for smoking-related
illness costs the community 12.7 billion Australian dollars
(nearly 10 billion U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
The federal government has committed 7 million Australian
dollars (5.32 million U.S. dollars) over two years to the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The campaign includes television and print advertisements and
practical support for smokers who want to quit. The television ads
use graphic images which show how smoking damages a person's
health.
</P>
<P>
"This is a determined effort by governments, and supported by
the Australian Cancer Society, the Australian Heart Foundation,
the Australian Medical Association and the College of General
Practitioners," the minister added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
