<HEADLINE> Singapore Welcomes IMS-GT Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 12 (Xinhua) --Singapore today welcomed
Indonesia's offer to include five more of its provinces into the
Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle (IMS-GT).
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister of Trade and Industry Lee Yock Suan said
this at a one-day Ministerial Meeting of IMS-GT in Jahor Baharu,
370 km southeast of Kuala Lumpur, according to reports reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian provinces to be included into the growth
triangle are Bengkulu, Jambi, Lampung, South Sumatera and West
Kalimantan, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
With the inclusions, the IMS-GT will expand its geographical
area from 208,000 square km to 565,000 square km and its market
size from 15 million to 34 million people.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Singapore, the IMS-GT growth triangle presently
covers Riau and West Sumetera of Indonesia and Malaysia's states
of Negeri Sembilan, Melaka (Malacca), Johor and Pahang.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the IMS-GT region received more than 8 billion U.S.
dollars in foreign direct investment (FDI).
</P>
<P>
The Singapore minister urged the IMS-GT to continue to sharpen
its competitive edge and improve the investment climate for
investors.
</P>
<P>
"We must continue to work together and maintain a pro-business
environment to allow businesses to prosper. We must streamline
government regulations and procedures to make it easier to do
businesses here," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said is up to member countries to turn the IMS-GT's strong
potential into benefits for both the business community and the
people in the region.
</P>
<P>
The IMS-GT, part of the broader framework of ASEAN cooperation,
would benefit from the formation of the ASEAN Free Trade Area
(AFTA) and the development of growth triangles would in turn
enhance ASEAN integration, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Being three close neighbors within ASEAN, we (Singapore,
Indonesia and Malaysia) can set the pace for forging economic
links within ASEAN," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz and Indonesia's Minister for Production and Distribution
Hartarto also attended the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
