<HEADLINE> Marital Status Steady in Hainan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Only 3.5 percent of the residents
in Hainan, one of China's most open and economically-developed
provinces, said that they are not satisfied with their marriages,
a recent survey shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted in China's southern island province of
Hainan, revealed that more than 91 percent of the respondents
are satisfied or basically satisfied with their marriages.
</P>
<P>
Most respondents believe that love and harmony are the most
important factors for a family, and money should not take an
important position in dealing with family relations, according to
the survey conducted by the Hainan Provincial Women's Federation.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that traditional value still dominates family
life. Some 63 percent of the respondents said that they have
maintained a good relationship between themselves and their
mothers-in-law. Only 1.9 percent said they are in a bad
relationship with their mothers-in-laws.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that there is less family violence in
Hainan families, and 94 percent of the respondents said that they
would turn to the legal means to protect themselves if their
rights and interests are infringed.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the respondents said that the husband
and wife should share household chores, and 62 percent believed
that a family's earnings should be put together and used
freely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus Links up Villages in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Wang Xixu, a 62-year old man
living in Cuijia Village, Huantai County in Shandong province,
never dreamed of having a regular bus stop nearby his house
located in one of the most remote parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
Now he has got the chance because Huantai, which covers 510 sq
km and has a population of 470,000, has become one of the few
counties in the whole country to link up its villages with regular
bus services.
</P>
<P>
"I used to get to the market or county town by riding a
bicycle," said Wang, "and it wasn't much fun on rainy days."
</P>
<P>
In November 1995, one year after Huantai achieved its goal to
connect all the county's 343 villages with asphalt-covered roads, a
well-managed inter-village bus network came into being.
</P>
<P>
The inter-village bus system has boosted the growth of the
county economy. Numerous factories and household-based businesses
have sprung up in this traditionally agricultural county. In
1996, the county's industrial output stood at 6.19 billion yuan,
up 32.7 percent compared with that of two years before.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the convenient passenger-transporting system has
helped over 80,000 excess rural laborers in Huantai go to other
parts of the country to find jobs. Last year, these farmer-turned
-workers brought home 628 million yuan, up 36.3 percent over the
figure of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a fledgling tourism industry has started in
Huantai -- a direct benefit brought by the bus service. In
1996 alone, some 800,000 domestic and overseas tourists traveled
to the county and spent eight million yuan there.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Communications told Xinhua that
the ministry has for long promoted the policy of encouraging
localities to develop passenger-transport means in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
They stress that it is economic reform and increasing rural
demands which have stimulated development in the respect. "So we
have never regarded the bus service a government enforced effort,"
they said.
</P>
<P>
However, consistent efforts by both central and local
governments to develop road networks in the countryside have paved
the way for the rural bus service, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
"All buses in Huantai are privately-owned and managed," said an
official from the county's transport bureau, "but they are
under strict supervision from the government."
</P>
<P>
"Those who violate rules will be deprived of their licenses,
and meanwhile, to maintain a reasonable profit-making level, the
number of buses involved in the network has been strictly
controlled," he said, noting that over 50 applications for
licenses were turned down by his office.
</P>
<P>
A bus that joins the service can generate around 20,000 yuan
per year in net profits to its owner, said the official.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Zhiqiang, Director of the Highway Management
Department under the Ministry of Communications, inter-village bus
networks, covering all local villages, have been formed in only 43
counties in the country. However, many counties are working hard
to reach the goal, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, according to Zhang, China had 370,000 buses
in regular, public service throughout the country, of which 45
percent were operating in rural areas. Meanwhile, 100,000
taxi cabs operate in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, rural passengers accounted for 60 percent of the
total handled by land passenger carriers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that, at present, 95 percent of small towns
as well as 74 percent of villages have been hooked up to the
network of bus services across the country. China has 16,000 bus
stations acting as hubs on the network.
</P>
<P>
The ministry hopes to make 95 percent of small towns and 80
percent of villages accessible by regular passenger bus services by
2000, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
