<HEADLINE> UN Agencies to Combat Spread of HIV in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations agencies
in Tanzania have placed the problem of the deadly Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) in their top development agenda in an
effort to combat the spread of HIV in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to local press today, UNICEF representative in
Tanzania and Seychelles Agnes Aidoo told reporters here on
Wednesday that the UN agencies working in the country have take
HIV/AIDS problem seriously and will put it high at their
development programs.
</P>
<P>
She said six UN agencies, including UNICEF, UNDP, WHO and
others, last year established a family program to combat the
spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
They have together launched a joint program known as UNAIDS,
and its major task is to fight the deadly disease by mobilizing
resources and expertise.
</P>
<P>
The UN official said around six million people in the world
have died in the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
She added that over 20 million people in the world are living
with HIV, the virus which causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is one of the most serious AIDS-hit African
countries. At present there is more than 800,000 people with HIV
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
