<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Retorts Japan's Criticism of Hanson Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Deputy Prime Minister
Tim Fischer hit back today at Japan for its criticism against
Australia's handling of human rights and Hanson issues, saying
Japan has one extreme group with a very unreformed view with
regard to World War II.
</P>
<P>
In his bid to defend Australia's handling of the Pauline Hanson
issue, the deputy prime minister said Japan also has extreme
organizations which his government does not feel happy about.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review reported Wednesday Japan has
softened its support for Australia's role in Asia after doubts
were expressed by a Japanese Foreign Ministry official about the
direction of the race debate and the government's handling of
human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
The official expressed surprise at the way in which the debate
over Pauline Hanson's comments has been allowed to drag on and not
dealt with quickly by the federal government, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"We were embarrassed when Australia opposed Myanmar's entry
into the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and the
way it was handled," said the official.
</P>
<P>
Japan Wednesday denied it was softening support for Australia's
role in Asia and said views expressed by the Japanese official did
not represent the official policy.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Embassy issued a statement reaffirming support for
Australia's participation in this year's Asia-Europe meeting as an
Asian member, currently a major focus of Australia's diplomacy in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister told the Australian Broadcasting
Corp. AM program today, "I remind Japan ... that we have
difficulties with some aspects and elements of their more extreme
organizations".
</P>
<P>
"I acknowledge also that they are a democracy with freedom of
speech, so is Australia; there are things you must accept as you
get with the bilateral relationship," said Fischer.
</P>
<P>
"One extreme group has a very unreformed view with regard to
World War II. I don't like that," he added.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister, who is also the country's trade
minister, did not say which group he was referring to.
</P>
<P>
"I am not going to dwell on it because what I am focusing on
it as minister for trade is building up the overall momentum of
the bilateral relationship between Australia and Japan," Fischer
said.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday night, Fisher told an institute of company directors
meeting in Melbourne that education and tourism were the
Australian industries most likely to be negatively affected by
overseas publicity about Hanson.
</P>
<P>
"The Pauline Hanson agenda is destructive of Australian jobs.
No ifs, no buts, it should be seen that way," Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
"We have over 50 billion Australian dollars (38 billion U.S.
dollars) of our export trade directed at Asia and each and every
one of the negative stories she generates about Asia are picked up
by (Australia's trade) competitors and faxed through the networks
of Asia," He said.
</P>
<P>
Independent MP Pauline Hanson has been advocating reduction in
intake of Asian immigrants and an end to foreign investment in
Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
