<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Restructuring to Boost Science Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Most of Chinese scientists and
engineers in research institutions, who used to launch research
programs according to state plans, now have to seek
market-oriented research projects.
</P>
<P>
Only a number of them can be engaged in state-funded basic
research and high-tech projects.
</P>
<P>
The present restructuring is deemed as a strategic
transformation by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), China's
top research organ with 123 institutions and 12 branches.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yumin, CAS Deputy Secretary-General, said among 70,000
researchers in the CAS, about 10,000 have moved to high-tech
enterprises and half of the personnel have shifted from the
research of basic sciences to projects of regional economic
development and market-oriented ones.
</P>
<P>
Song Yong, head of Restructuring Department of the State Science
and Technology Commission (SSTC) noted that starting from this
year, China began an overall restructure reform in state and
ministry level research institutions all over the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the restructuring would not "produce laid-off
scientists." The problem is that too many scientists were engaged
in basic researches under the planned economic system.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that "China is greatly in need of
scientists, they are far more from being outnumbered. The reform
is aimed at abolishing repeated research organs and establish new
ones according to the world trend and economic development."
</P>
<P>
China now has 1,058 research organs at state or ministry levels
which employed over 600,000 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructuring to Boost Science Development  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics from CAS show that the annual per capita research
fund for a US scientist or an engineer is 160,000 US dollars,
190,000 in Japan, 36,000 in the Republic of Korea, but 6,600 in
China.
</P>
<P>
The research institutions under the Ministry of Communications
will lead the rest of China in experimenting such restructuring. An
official with the ministry said the Ministry of Communications
will establish three research centers, namely shipping, highway
transport and water transport engineering by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The researchers will be selected from the original 16 research
organs under the ministry. The rest of the research organs will
either join the enterprise groups of the ministry or turn into
science and technology oriented enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The CAS Institute of Applied Mathematics will also spearhead
such reform in the CAS. Zhang Xiangsun, director of the institute
said the total number of researchers in his institute has been
reduced from 120 to some 80 after some incompetent research staffs
quit here and other aged scientists retire.
</P>
<P>
He explained that his institute has imposed a contract system
for the young researchers while providing "iron rice bowls" for
the old.
</P>
<P>
The director said, the newly invited researchers, chosen from
people with doctor's degree by exams, concentrate on their
research programs despite relatively low income.
</P>
<P>
The young researchers here are encouraged to have short-time
study or work in the western countries to master the global trend and
increase their income at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Sang Yong said the SSTC will not issue any compulsive orders on
the reform of the research institutions, but such restructuring
will be implemented step by step.
</P>
<P>
He believed that after the overall restructuring, China's
research organs will become more competitive in science
development and viable for self-development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abbot Hongyi Museum Being Built in Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Work on a museum dislaying the
life of late Abbot Hongyi, eminent monk and one of the forerunners
of Chinese modern culture, has begun in Quanzhou, Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Quanzhou is where Hongyi stayed and taught Buddhist scripture.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the 1,000-square-meter museum is expected to be
completed in three years. On display will be Abbot Hongyi's
Calligraphy works, seal cuttings, musical instruments and a large
number of scriptures brought back from Japan and a number of his
articles he used, such as straw sandals, oil lamps.
</P>
<P>
Hongyi, who was born in 1880 in Tianjin and passed away in
October, 1942 in Quanzhou, was named Li Shutong before becoming a
monk. He was considered a great art master and his life was both
legendary and remarkable.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 38, he was initiated into monkhood and began
practising Buddhism. He did a thorough study of Buddhism and
became a representative of "luzong," a modern Buddhist sect
in China.
</P>
<P>
From November 1932 to October 1942, He settled down in southern
part of Fujian Province and taught in temples in Quanzhou,
Jinjiang, Hui'an and Yongchun.
</P>
<P>
Cultural relics of Buddhism in Quanzhou will also be exhibited
at the museum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
