<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Congress Resolution Welcomed by Israel, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Congress resolution
recognizing united Jerusalem as Israel's capital has been praised
by Israel and criticized by the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives voted 406-17 Tuesday to
recognize Jerusalem as the undivided capital of Israel, despite
opposition by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The house also voted to provide 100 million U.S. dollars for
moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, who see East Jerusalem as the capital of a
future Palestinian state, sharply criticized the resolution,
which they said would hurt the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
PNA Higher Education Minister Hanan Ashrawi described the
resolution as obvious support for Israel, saying it "puts a big
nail in the coffin of the peace process and the credibility of
the U.S. as a peace broker."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, members of the Israeli government welcomed the
resolution, which was, in their word, "obviously reflecting the
will of the American people."
</P>
<P>
"We are delighted that the Congress has recognized Jerusalem
as the undivided capital of Israel and it will remain forever,"
said David Bar-Ilan, Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's media
adviser.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Ilan also expressed happiness at the prospective transfer
of the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem "in 1999."
</P>
<P>
Most countries in the world, including the U.S., have not
recognized Israel's annexation of East Jerusalem immediately
after the Six Day War in 1967.
</P>
<P>
It has been the position of successive U.S. government that the
city must never be divided again, but its future must be settled
through negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
