<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 07:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Receive U.S. Aircraft in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 12 (Xinhua) - Jordan will receive the first batch
of 16 F-16 fighters from the United States in December as part of
a military aid package worth 300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This was announced late on Wednesday night by Chief of Staff
of the Jordanian Armed Forces Abdul Hafiz Miree Kaabneh at the
conclusion of the 3-week long Jordanian-U.S. joint military
exercises codenamed "Infinite Moonlight 1997."
</P>
<P>
Jordan has dispatched its pilots to the U.S. to be trained on
the aircraft, Kaabneh said.
</P>
<P>
"we will upgrade and improve our military relations, which
are already deep-rooted, as much as we can. The exercise we
witnessed is a sign of our cooperation to preserve the mutual
interests of our both countries," the military chief said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Jordanian Armed Forces will conduct more
exercises with British and French forces and U.S. troops this
year as part of the kingdom's endeavor to strengthen combat
effectiveness of its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The joint war game, the second one between the two sides
within the year, was conducted following the failure of the
recent international efforts to reactivate the deadlocked
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The exercises were carried out in the Qatraneh desert, some 90
kilometers south of the Jordanian capital of Amman.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which is given by the U.S. the status of non-ally of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), has the access to
U.S. military assistance.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Jordan received a 100 million dollars
U.S. military aid as part of a total of 300 million dollars'
assistance pledged by the U.S. administration.
</P>
<P>
The aid included 18 UH-1H helicopters, 50 M60A3 tanks, 250
M1008 and M1009 trucks, 2 MK-4 personal boats, an air-sea rescue
vessel as well as machine-guns and 1,000 night-vision goggles.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 200 million dollars of the assistance will be
spent on 16 F-16 jet fighters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
