<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Industrial Growth Slowdown to Continue: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The slowdown in India's
industrial growth will be bottomed out only by the end of the
current financial year (April 1997-March 1998) and in the first
quarter of 1998-99 fiscal year when the industry will grow between
10.5 and 11.5 percent, a study says.
</P>
<P>
The study, published by the National Herald today and it covers
over 175 large, medium and small corporates having a cross section
of business interest, also indicates that the present slowdown is
a temporary phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
This trend will be reversed due to the combined effect of the
just-adopted budget for 1997-98, the new credit policy, relaxation
in the external commercial borrowings and a host of other steps
which are being taken by the United Front government led by Prime
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral.
</P>
<P>
The study is based on certain assumptions -- the rate of
borrowing would come down to 17 to 18 percent and inflation would
be hovering around 6 to 7 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
