<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Win Game Five to Lead Finals 3-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SALT LAKE CITY, June 11 (Xinhua) -- the Chicago Bulls,
four-time NBA champions, took the crucial Game Five of the NBA
Finals Wednesday night, beating the Utah Jazz 90:88 to move within
one game win of their fifth NBA championship in seven years.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan's last-minute three-pointer shot contributed to
the victory as it gained a three-point margin that the Jazz found
hard to get enough time to make a balance.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, who started slowly, got only four points after the
first quarter, but he stormed an offensive in the fourth, scoring
15 of his 38 points.
</P>
<P>
With Utah leading 85-84, Jordan made the first of two free
throws to tie the score and soon received a pass from Scottie
Pippen and made the wide-open three-pointer from the left side to
gain the Bulls a 88-85 lead.
</P>
<P>
It was a key game for both teams as the two made 2:2 even in
the last four Finals, particularly for the home team Jazz as it
will fight a uphill battle in the next one or two games at Bulls'
home -- Chicago.
</P>
<P>
Like the last games, the two teams, champions of the West and
East of the United States, played aggressively throughout the
game. The Jazz gained an uphand all the way until the last
minutes. It led a 16-point advance in the second quarter before
the bulls, led by Jordan, regained their loss.
</P>
<P>
The two teams inched up their scores in the last minutes after
the Bulls balanced the score by Jordan's two three-pointers.
</P>
<P>
Pippen added 17 points and Luc Longley 12 for the Bulls. Karl
Malone scored 19 points and Greg Ostertag and John Stockton added
13 apiece for the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls hope to wrap up their fifth title with a victory at
home in Game Six on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
