<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Bangladesh Agree on Power Exchange Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- India and Bangladesh have
recently agreed on a project to export power to each other in a
bid to optimize the resources available in the two countries, the
Times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a high-level meeting held in Manila recently under the aegis
of the Asian Development Bank (ADB), the two countries agreed to
enter into the power-sharing arrangement, initially for five
years.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the ADB has offered to fund the
project designed to facilitate export of power from eastern India
to western Bangladesh and from eastern Bangladesh to northeastern
India.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, each country is to construct all necessary
facilities up to its international border.
</P>
<P>
Apart from exchange of electricity, the two sides also showed
keen interest in cooperation in sectors like gas and
communications.
</P>
<P>
Eastern India has surplus power which creates problems of
over-voltage and high frequency. Power-deficit northeastern states
like Tripura and Mizoram face the opposite problem of low voltage
and low frequency.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, which is between the two regions, has most of its
generating capacity concentrated in the eastern part whereas the
demand is concentrated in the western part.
</P>
<P>
Difficult topography comes in the way of transfer of power from
eastern Bangladesh to western Bangladesh. The project will not
only help the two countries overcome the problems of frequency and
voltage, but also lead to reduction in transmission losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
