<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Shorten Visa Service Process for Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to cut its
lengthy process for granting visas for foreign investors as a
measure to facilitate inflows of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Board of Investment, a state agency directly under
the Prime Minister's Office, will set up a new service center for
that purpose, where investors from 35 countries and regions will
be able to obtain a visa and work permit in three hours.
</P>
<P>
Under the new measure, investors eligible for a one-year visa
and work permit must invest at least 2 million baht (80,000 U.S.
dollars) in Thailand, local newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign experts or professional managers can only come to
Thailand to work with a private firm with a registered capital of
at least 30 million baht (1.2 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Investors wanting a two-year visa and one-year work permit must
invest at least 10 million baht (400,000 dollars) in the country.
</P>
<P>
The visa and work permit can also be extended.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, investors from Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia,
the Philippines, Singapore, South Korea and Taiwan will be able to
enjoy the service.
</P>
<P>
In Europe, 19 countries including Britain, France, Germany,
Italy, Iceland, Denmark, Finland, Spain, Sweden and Switzerland
are covered.
</P>
<P>
For other continents, investors from Canada, the U.S.,
Australia, New Zealand, Israel, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and United
Arab Emirates are eligible.
</P>
<P>
Currently, foreign investors have to wait for three months to
obtain a visa and work permit in Thailand as they are subject to
the approval of three state agencies -- the Board of Investment,
the Immigration Office and the Interior Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
