<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Scholars Rap U.S. Interference in Thai law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thai traditional medicine scholars
Wednesday accused the United States of interfering Thailand's
internal affairs as it tended to block a Thai draft bill to
protect local medicine wisdom, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Pennapa Subcharoen, director of the National Institute of Thai
Traditional Medicine, expressed surprise over a U.S. warning that
the draft bill, which is in the final stage of the drafting
process, could violate global trade rules.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill is aimed at protecting local villagers from
being exploited by multinational companies, Pennapa said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign countries, including the U.S., could also benefit from
the bill as research and development of traditional medicine could
be more institutionalized, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. needs no worry that its powerful pharmaceutical
industry and researchers would no longer have access to Thailand's
rich resources, she added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy in Bangkok earlier this year sent a letter to
Thailand's Department of Intellectual Property to express concern
that the bill could violate global trade rules and affect future
research of Thai traditional medicine.
</P>
<P>
The letter reportedly also required clarification on 11 points
concerning the registration of traditional Thai medicines.
</P>
</TEXT>
