<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Backed for Second-Term LDP Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto is certain to be reelected president of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) after party leaders agreed
Wednesday night to support his bid for a second term, the media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
With no challengers on the horizon, party leaders expect
Hashimoto to be reelected without a vote in early September when
his current two-year term expires, LDP officials were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The LDP leaders, including Secretary General Koichi Kato,
pledged party solidarity under Hashimoto to reform Japan's
bureaucracy and state finances.
</P>
<P>
They also envisioned maintaining the current alliance with the
Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New Party Sakigake, the LDP's
two non-cabinet allies.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto was first elected LDP president in September 1995
while serving as international trade and industry minister
under then Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama of the SDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
