<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka, Qatar to Develop Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka and Qatar plan to enter
into bilateral agreements on economic and trade cooperation,
investment protection and avoidance of double taxation.
</P>
<P>
This follows the visit to Qatar by Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Laksman Kadirgamar on June 7 when he opened the country's new
mission there, according to a Foreign Ministry news release today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries set up diplomatic relations in June last
year.
</P>
<P>
The release said during the visit, Kadirgamar and his Qatari
counterpart agreed to expand cooperation in new areas such as
investment, trade, tourism and infrastructure development between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
When his meeting with Kadirgamar, Qatar Prime Minister Dheikh
Abdulla Bin Khalifa al-Thani said his country is interested in
securing more flights to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to exchange information on the
promotion of Sri Lankan overseas workers in Qatar. There are some
35,000 Sri Lankans now working in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar briefed the Qatar Chamber of Commerce and Industry
(QCCI) on the incentives and facilities offered by Sri Lanka to
foreign investors and the importance of the private sector
participation and economic and commercial relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The QCCI expressed their interest in the establishment of joint
ventures with Sri Lanka and it would send a private sector
delegation to Sri Lanka for that purpose.  
</P>
</TEXT>
