<HEADLINE> Nepal, Germany Sign Agreement on Air Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Nepal and
Germany have signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) on
operating air services between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, the two governments agreed to operate nine
two-way passenger flights and six cargo flights every week between
Nepal and Germany, a joint communique issued here said today.
</P>
<P>
With the signing of the MOU, private sector airlines in Nepal
will be allowed to operate flights to Germany, trade sources said.
</P>
<P>
The MOU was signed here Wednesday by representatives of the two
country's air authorities.
</P>
<P>
A Nepali civil aviation official said on the occasion said that
the liberal aviation policies adopted by the two countries would
make Visit Nepal Year 1998, the official tourism promotion program
aimed at attracting 500,000 foreign tourists next year, a success.
</P>
<P>
German officials disclosed that a German airline will operate
air services to Kathmandu in the near future after the German
national flag carrier Lufthansa stopped its Nepal operation last
month due to financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nepali Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation,
Nepal has signed air service agreements with 22 countries and the
state-owned Royal Nepal Airlines (RNA) has been operating with 12
destinations in 10 countries.  
</P>
