<HEADLINE> Four Detained in Money Laundering Crackdown in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Four Italian construction magnates
were arrested, with their apartment blocks confiscated and assets
of 11 companies seized, when Finance Guards police cracked down on
a major Mafia money laundering ring in Palermo today.
</P>
<P>
In an operation coded as Dirty Buildings in Palermo, Sicilia,
the police detained Vincenzo Rappa, Francesco Pecora, Salvatore
Sbeglia and Domenico Graziano for questioning for suspected
collaboration with the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
Filippo Rappa, son of the 75-year-old Vincenzo Rappa, a
well-known builder, was also detained. Filippo, 54, is a former
Christian Democrat city councillor and owner of Trm, a leading
local TV station.
</P>
<P>
Others placed in custody included two father and son business
partnerships, Domenico and Camillo Graziano, 60 and 30
respectively, and Francesco and Giovanni Pecora, 58 and 24
respectively. Custody orders were also served on two car dealers,
Giuseppe Curcio and Mario Umbertone.
</P>
<P>
Judicial sources said preventive custody orders were also
served on two jailed Mafia bosses, Raffaele Ganci and Francesco
Rappa. Ganci was arrested on June 10, 1993 as the right-hand man
of Boss of Bosses, Salvatore Riina.
</P>
<P>
As the list of those detained lengthened, judicial sources said
in the late morning that seven custody orders had now been served
on jailed Mafiosi.
</P>
<P>
The investigators say the construction companies whose assets
were seized may have been used to launder a large part of the
Mafia's millions of dollars in revenue from drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
The finance police have combed through thousands of pages of
company and bank accounts to find clues and they said they also
enjoyed information from a witness.
</P>
<P>
One of the confiscated companies was Guido Umbertini SpA, which
is well-known for rebuilding Palermo's Favorita stadium for the
1990 World Cup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
