<HEADLINE> Cool Summer Expected in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A cool summer and long rainy season
is expected in Japan this year as the so-called El Nino phenomenon
has apparently returned after a four year hiatus, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Abnormally high temperatures recorded last month in the Pacific
Ocean around the equator suggest the phenomenon, which causes
abnormal weather patterns across the globe, has returned, the
report quoted Meteorological Agency officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
El Nino typically causes temperatures in the Pacific Ocean off
the coast of Peru to rise one to two, or sometimes two to five
degrees higher than normal. The phenomenon lasts for one to one
and half years and occurs every two to seven years, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists are concerned that El Nino could bring a
relatively cool summer and long rainy season this year in Japan,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Activists Against NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A group of influential U.S. social
activists will stage mass protests against NATO expansion during
the western military alliance's summit in Madrid next month.
</P>
<P>
The planned demonstrations were announced today by Cora Weiss,
one of the leading figures of a group called Action For Peace.
</P>
<P>
The massive expenses involved in NATO 's eastward enlargement,
estimated at between 25 billion and 125 billion U.S. dollars, was
an important reason for the group's opposition to the plan, Weiss
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Weiss and her colleagues are on a visit to Moscow to mobilize
international support for the action against NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
Russia has consistently opposed NATO's eastward expansion,
saying the move will threaten its own security.
</P>
<P>
Members from Action For Peace have already been to London and
Brussels and will head for the Polish capital Warsaw after their
Moscow visit. Poland is widely expected to be one of the first
wave of countries to be invited to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
Michael Newlin, another activist, said he believes NATO
expansion will increase the threat of nuclear confrontation.
</P>
<P>
If the group fails in its efforts to check NATO's scheme, they
will keep a close watch on the process of implementing the accord
on Russia-NATO relations, said Newlin, who is an adviser to the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and former
U.S. ambassador to Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Russia and NATO signed an agreement defining their
relationship, cooperation and security matters in Paris on May 27,
a deal seen as paving the way for NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Madrid summit is expected to finalize the list of new NATO
members, although they won't be admitted until 1999 when NATO
celebrates its 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials have reiterated their opposition to NATO
enlargement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
