<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economy Expected to Have Sustainable Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economy will start
recovering this year and achieve sustainable growth in 1998, about
a year behind most developed countries in the Asia-Pacific region,
noted economists predict.
</P>
<P>
Suhadi Mangkusuwondo, a member of the Indonesian National
Committee of the Pacific Economic Cooperation Council (INCPEC),
said the one-year lag of Indonesia's economic recovery was because
economic development in Indonesia followed trends in Japan and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia and several other developing countries will
experience this lag," he said at a meeting Wednesday at the Center
for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS), which was attended
by several well-known economists.
</P>
<P>
Quoting an INCPEC's Pacific Economic Outlook, an annual
short-term forecast of 20 East Asian, North American and Latin
economies, Suhadi said most Pacific Rim economies were expected to
have a slightly faster economic growth this year and next year --
marked by low inflation rates -- following a "soft landing" in
1995 and a recovery last year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's 1994 economic growth stood at 7.5 percent and rose
to 8.2 percent in 1995 before slowing down to 7.8 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted economic growth at 7.3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
"The soft landing by most countries in the Asia-Pacific began
in 1995, the recovery in 1996, and the forecast for sustained
growth in 1997 and 1998 reflects the strong macro-economic
fundamentals and enhanced economic management capabilities in most
of the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia achieved a soft landing last year, after it went
through rapid growth in 1995 which caused an overheating of the
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
