<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czechs Keep Title as World's Top Beer Drinkers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic was the world's
top beer drinking nation last year, winning the title for the
fourth year in a row.
</P>
<P>
The average person in the Czech Republic drank about 160 liters
of beer in 1996, 28 liters more than Germany, which was knocked
off the top perch in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Beer consumption per person in Germany was 132 liters last
year, four liters lower than in 1995, because of cool weather. The
world's third biggest beer-consuming nation is Denmark, whose
population downs an average 121 liters each year, the media here
reported.
</P>
<P>
Beer is the national drink in the Czech Republic where it's
regarded as "liquid bread." It's a must at gatherings of family
and friends and at state banquets.
</P>
<P>
Beer is also part of the country's social fabric. Just as
Chinese people enjoy sitting in tea houses drinking tea, Czech
people enjoy sinking a few pints in a bar or pub.
</P>
<P>
In a country of just 10 million people, there are more than 70
large and medium-sized breweries and total annual beer output is
1.8 billion liters.
</P>
<P>
In addition to producing for the domestic market, breweries
export beer to Slovakia, Poland, Germany, Austria and the United
States. Beer has now become a pillar export industry in terms of
foreign exchange earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
