<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lianyungang Nuclear Power Project Proceeds Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIANYUNGANG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Preparation work has been
proceeding smoothly for the construction of a six million kw
nuclear power project in Lianyungang, a port city in east China's
Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
According to an engineer in charge of the construction, they
will build the nuclear power plant with the state-of-the-art
technologies as they pursue the government policy of "safety and
quality comes first" in developing the nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear power plant, to be equipped with Russia-made
VVER-1000 reactors and German Simens-made control system, will be
built in three phases.
</P>
<P>
For the first phase, two pressurized Russia-made VVER-1000
reactors will be installed and put into operation in 2004 and 2005
respectively, and running parallel in timing is the second-phase
which will focus on infrastructure of the projects.
</P>
<P>
When operational, the nuclear power plant is expected to be
able to generate 15 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
About 30 billion yuan will be spent on the first-phase of
construction. Lianyungang Nuclear Power Co. Ltd. will be
responsible for building and operation of the nuclear power
plant. The company was jointly invested by China National Nuclear
Corp., Jiangsu International Trust and Investment Corp., East
China Electric Power Corp. and Jiangsu Provincial Electric Power
Company.
</P>
<P>
A special leading group for the construction of the power
plant, mainly composed of officials from Jiangsu provincial
government, Lianyungang city and relevant departments, was earlier
announced to be established to help coordinate the building of the
nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
China has so far built two nuclear power stations, namely, the
Qinshan Nuclear Power Plant in east China's Zhejiang province and
the Nuclear Power Plant at Daya Bay near Shenzhen in south China's
Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China will also build another nuclear power plant in
Ling'ao of Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
China's nuclear power output reached 14.3 billion kilowatt
hours (kwh) in 1996, up 12 percent over the previous year,
according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Plant in Zhejiang generated 2.23
billion kwh, while the Daya Bay Plant in Guangdong produced 12.11
billion kwh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Chairman Returns from Europe Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), returned home this morning by a special plane
from an official goodwill visit to Portugal, Greece and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Among Those greeting Li and his party at the Great Hall of the
People are Hu Jintao, a Standing Committee member of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and
a member of the Secretariat of the CPC Central Committee, Wu
Xueqian, Wang Zhaoguo and Ngapoi Ngawang Jigme, vice-chairmen of
the CPPCC National Committee, and other Party and government
officials, as well as ambassadors of the three European countries
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Li's entourage also arrived by the same plane. They are Zhu
Xun, a member of the Standing Committee and secretary-general of
the CPPCC National Committee, Cheng Siwei, a Standing Committee
member of the CPPCC National Committee and chairman of the Central
Committee of the China Democratic National Construction
Association, Wang Daming, a member of the CPPCC National Committee
and chairman of the Beijing Municipal Committee of the CPPCC, Doje
Cedain, a Standing Committee member of the CPPCC National
Committee and director-general of the China Tibetan Studies
Center, and Li Zhaoxing, vice-foreign minister. 
</P>
