<HEADLINE> President: Belarus-Russia Union Formally Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko today announced the formal establishment of the
Belarus-Russia Union, following the exchange of legal documents
ratifying a union treaty and a union charter on integrating the
two former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko made the announcement at a ceremony to exchange the
ratification documents in Minsk, capital of Belarus, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who exchanged the
documents with his Belarussian counterpart, Ivan Antonovich, said
the union would become an attractive model of integration within
the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) made up of former
Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Lukashenko and Russian President Boris Yeltsin
signed into law the union treaty and the union charter, following
their ratification by the parliaments of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Most Russians and Belarussians support integration moves
between their countries, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The union treaty and the union charter were signed by Yeltsin
and Lukashenko in Moscow in early April and late May,
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
