<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Maintain Close Economic Ties with HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said today that Malaysia would continue to
have close trade, economic and cultural relations with Hong Kong
as they exist now after China resumes the exercise of sovereignty
over Hong Kong on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
With the establishment of a consulate general in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region from July 1, 1997, Malaysia will
continue to have its presence there. This is a "clear indicator of
Malaysia's confidence in the mutually beneficial relationship that
it enjoys with Hong Kong, the minister said in a written interview
with Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, we believe that Hong Kong's position as a top
international commercial and financial center should be further
consolidated and promoted by China as it would complement and
strengthen China's own dynamic economic development and progress,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the forthcoming return of Hong Kong to China is
"undoubtedly of historical significance" and Malaysia is "happy"
to see the event taking place in a peaceful and amicable manner.
</P>
<P>
He believed the resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong by China should not affect Malaysia's overall excellent
relations with either China or Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Our existing close and friendly relations with China will
continue and be further strengthened as our substantive economic
links with Hong Kong would also constitute an important component
of our overall relationship with China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the present relationship between Malaysia and
China, the minister, who paid an official visit to China last
month, said he achieved his main objective during his recent
visit, namely, to further strengthen Malaysia-China relations
through the meetings with China's top leaders, and to deepen his
own understanding of China.
</P>
<P>
He said as Malaysia is the current chairman of the ASEAN
Standing Committee, his visit also enabled him to consult with
China on overall ASEAN-China cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Describing the current Malaysia-China relations "very good" and
"extremely well" developed in recent years, he said, "Malaysia is
happy with the momentum and progress in its bilateral relations
with China."
</P>
<P>
The minister said the exchange of high level visits, in
particular, reflects the seriousness and commitment of the two
sides to forging closer cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia wishes to continue the momentum in developing and
fostering bilateral cooperation with China in various fields, he
said, adding there is enormous potential to further enhance trade
and economic cooperation between both countries for mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
The business communities from both countries should be more
adventurous in exploring opportunities that both countries could
offer, he said.
</P>
<P>
With economic cooperation between Malaysia and China continuing
to record an upward trend in tandem with the momentum in the
growing political relations, he said, "I am of the view that
prospects for Malaysia-China relations are very bright indeed."
</P>
<P>
He said as Malaysia and China share similar aspirations and
objectives for lasting peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific
region, both countries can work closely to promote peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The increasing bilateral economic cooperation between the two
countries should also further contribute towards the dynamic
economic growth and development currently enjoyed by the region
into the next century, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
