<HEADLINE> Colombian Guerrillas Accused of Kidnapings in Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Colombian guerrillas and gangsters
have obtained nearly 20 million U.S. dollars from kidnapings and
extortions committed in Venezuela in 1996, said the Internal
Policy Committee of the Chamber of Deputies (lower house of
parliament).
</P>
<P>
Of that amount, 90 percent was sent to the Colombian Insurgence
and 10 percent to Colombian criminals who committed crimes in
Venezuelan border areas, the committee said in a report published
today.
</P>
<P>
Colombian rebels obtained 14 million dollars through extortions
and 3.67 million through the kidnapping of Venezuelan farmers and
cattle ranchers, while gangsters obtained 3 millions from both
activities.
</P>
<P>
The committee ruled out the possibility of a dialogue with the
Colombian guerrillas since that could lead to greater conflicts,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The document proposed that the Colombian guerrillas be declared
a regional threat to democratic institutions and suggested that
police and military forces prevent and control crimes in border
towns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
