<HEADLINE> Finland Provides $6.4 Million in Humanitarian Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Finland has decided to provide a
total of 32 million Finnish marks (about 6.4 million U.S. dollars)
in humanitarian aid to help the poor in war-torn countries, the
Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
International organizations, such as the United Nations
Children's Fund, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, and the
World Food Program as well as the Finnish Red Cross, are in charge
of carrying out the aid project, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The beneficiaries include Sudan, those in the Great Lake area,
Burundi, Croatia, East Slovenia, and the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) area.
</P>
<P>
A senior Finnish official said that the countries of Africa,
Europe and the CIS, need the humanitarian aid, Finland must be
ready to rapidly respond to the grave situation in the areas. It
is a mark of a civilized country to provide humanitarian aid to
poor countries.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Finland had provided 100,000 Finnish marks
(about 20,000 dollars) to the newly-founded Mondlane fund of
Mozambique to help promote the country's safety and stability.
</P>
