<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Costa Rica Intensifies Highway Vigilance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica traffic police
authorities today intensified its vigilance over drunk-driving and
overspeeding on highways to reduce the mortality rate in highway
accidents in the country.
</P>
<P>
Drivers will be fined from 5,000 colons (21 U.S.dollars) to
20,000 colons (86 dollars) if they are found speeding or drinking
alcohol during driving.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents are one of the 10 main causes of death in the
country. In 1996, 260 people died in 42,872 traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
To reduce traffic accidents by 25 percent from now on to the
year 2000, the Costa Rican government has declared 1997 as the
Year of Prevention.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican President Jose Maria Figueres signed three highway
decrees Tuesday. Police will breathalize drivers suspected of
drunk-driving and impose a stricter control on renewal of a
driver's license.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents cause 86 million dollars in losses a year in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
