<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Mailmen Bear Heavy Load </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A recent investigation finds that
Beijing, the busiest postal hub in China, delivers 3,000 tons of
mail, parcels and newspapers each day, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The findings were revealed at a birthday meeting for Beijing
Postal Administration (BPA), which has named 1997 "Postal Service
Year" to celebrate the centenary of the founding of the capital
city's postal service.
</P>
<P>
A report based on the investigation, while endorsing the
achievement made by BPA, nontheless criticizes Beijing postmen for
loss of mail and publications.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, complaints from the city mailmen said too many
real estate developers neglect to apply for mail delivery and
pick-up, leaving their tenants high - literally - and without
their daily mail, according to the natioanl English newspaper.
</P>
<P>
A survey counted 29,389 highrise residential buildings in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, postal service was provided for residents of
27,559 high-rise buildings.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 1,830 have no mailboxes or no building numbers -
or no roads leading to the buildings.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Postal Administration (BPA) said that postal
development needs more understanding and support from
everyone. It's very difficult for the post office alone to solve
the problems.
</P>
<P>
The BPA built 15 new postal and telecom offices and set up 24
more with the help of other departments last year, said a BPA
official.
</P>
<P>
With a staff of nearly 20,000, the BPA serves a population of
11.65 million within an area of 16,800 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the total turnover of the postal services reached 815
million yuan (98.2 million US dollars) - up 17 percent above 1995
- and postal revenues were 1.23 billion yuan (148 million US
dollars)- up 27 percent over the same period of the previous
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
