<HEADLINE> Thailand, Singapore to Sign Human Resources Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Singapore will sign
an agreement on bolstering human resources in developing
countries, according to a Thai Foreign Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum of understanding on "third-country training"
will be signed by Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn and
his Singaporean counterpart S. Jayakumar during Singaporean Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong's visit to Thailand next week.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Thailand and Singapore would choose the
beneficiary countries, coach their experts and improve training
facilities, Thinnakorn Kannasutra, deputy director-general of the
Foreign Ministry's Information Department, was quoted today by
local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
They initially plan to launch two, two-month projects this
year, and will discuss other potential areas of cooperation after
the document is signed.
</P>
<P>
Goh Chok Tong will also discuss with Thai Prime Minister
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh a planned exchange program between the two
countries for government officials.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's proposal aimed to enhance relations among the
officials, determine new fields of cooperation, bolster
information exchanges and develop human resources, Thinnakorn
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
