<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Progress in Test-Tube Calf Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The University of Inner Mongolia in
north China produced its first test-tube calf this year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists hailed it as a major step forward in the
cattle in-vitro fertilization technology.
</P>
<P>
So far, the university's Experimental Animal Research Center
has obtained eight calves by using the in-vitro fertilization
technology on quality Australian cattle. The first seven calves
were born in Dalian in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
China listed research in cattle in-vitro fertilization
technology as a key project in its decade-long hi-tech development
program beginning in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The Experimental Animal Research Center has summed up a set of
mature test-tube calf techniques, and set up a modernized
laboratory in cooperation with the University of Melbourne in
1995. Fertilized embryos were shipped to China and transplanted
into Chinese cows after they are defrosted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more than 30 cows have been fertilized, eight of
which have made deliveries. The rest will make deliveries before
August this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
