<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Has A Part in Guarding Cleanness of Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China has attached great
importance to the military ports' environment and made marked
efforts to improve the cability of supervising, monitoring and
treating pollution in the ports.
</P>
<P>
The ports have set up a comprehensive system to supervise and
monitor the cleanness of the coastline and deal with pollutions,
according to Wang Kuicheng, a senior colonel of the Navy's
Logistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The navy's personnel, technology and equipment are capable of
understaking the environmental protection work in the ports on
their own, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The navy has set up 18 environment monitoring stations in its
military ports in 1985 with the approval of the Central Military
Commission, marking the beginning of its environmental efforts.
</P>
<P>
Grease is the main pollutants in the military ports. The
navy has developed a kind of vessels that can treat the grease
and built treatment stations in Lushun, Qingdao, Zhanjiang and
Shanghai. At present, the military ports can handle some 100 tons
of grease an hour. Monitoring ships are deployed in the ports to
check pollutants discharge.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, the navy's port monitoring and supervising
organ is a leading member of thcience
and technology information network of the Ministry of
Communications and national oceanographic monitoring network. The
navy has also participated in the revision of the national
environmental protection codes and international environmental
protection conventions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Seeks "Partnership" with Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has submitted a "white
paper" on Thai-Japanese economic relations which calls for the two
countries to develop a "partnership" in subregional cooperation
projects, according to a press release issued by the Thai Foreign
Ministry available today.
</P>
<P>
The document, which will be discussed in a review on economic
relations due to take place in Tokyo in August or September, was
handed to Japanese Ambassador Hiroshi Ota Tuesday by Thai Deputy
Foreign Minister Pitak Intrawithayanunt.
</P>
<P>
Pitak will head the Thai delegation at the conference and hold
preparatory talks on a scheduled visit to Japan by Thai Prime
Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh in early October, the press release
said.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, the third of its kind after publications in
1985 and 1991, says the development of a "partnership" and
"economic alliance" in subregional projects would bolster the
regional role of Japan and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The document cites the "economic hexagon" encompassing the
Mekong River countries of Myanmar, Cambodia, Laos, Thailand,
Vietnam and China, the growth triangle linking Thailand with
Malaysia and Indonesia, subregional road plans, and Thailand's
eastern and southern seaboard projects.
</P>
<P>
The document also calls for cooperation to reduce Thailand's
trade deficit with Japan, including access to the Japanese market
for tapioca products, frozen chicken, fresh shrimp, pork,
vegetables and fruit.
</P>
<P>
In investment, Thailand proposes being an industrial base for
Japan to produce vehicles, electrical and electronic products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
