<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: New Economic Center to Emerge in Southwest China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Authorities of Chongqing
have planned to build the city, China's largest, into an economic
power house in southwest China and the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River through a decade's efforts.
</P>
<P>
Located in the intersection between economically developed
coastal China and resource-rich western China, the city is
recognized an economic hub in China's vast inland areas and a key
river harbor in China's longest river, the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
After Chongqing was expanded and put directly under the
leadership of the central government, it was asked to "give full
play to its strategic location for speeding up overall social and
economic development in the region."
</P>
<P>
The city now occupies an area of 82,000 square kilometers and
has a population of 30.02 million.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities have mapped out their own development
program in accordance with the state guideline.
</P>
<P>
The annual gross domestic product (GDP) growth is set to reach
11 percent by the year of 2000. The city also planss to eradicate
poverty among its large rural population and form a new industrial
belt before 2000.
</P>
<P>
The longer-term targets set for 2010 are to quadruple its 1995
GDP and build up a medium-developed city in China in terms of
comprehensive economic strength.
</P>
<P>
Even though the city has registered a more than ten percent
growth rate for four years in a row, its GDP in 1995 was merely
101.3 billion yuan, at the lower middle level among major Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
Local experts believed the city can benefit from the Yangtze
River development strategy blueprinted by the central
government. The strategy aimed to gear up overall development in
the whole valley of the Yangtze River with Shanghai's Pudong New
Area as its locomotive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: New Economic Center to Emerge in Southwest China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Overseas investors in the past years have flocked to gain
foothold in the city, considered a springboard to enter China's
vast inland areas.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the city has approved 2,560 projects with
overseas investment. The capital actually utilized by the city
topped 2.81 billion US dollars. Overseas investment in the city
accounted to 15 percent of its total investment in fixed
assets. The city's foreign trade volume last year hit 1.41 billion
US dollars, or ten percent of the total GDP.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing's new municipal status turned the city more
attractive for overseas investors. The number of projects with
overseas investment approved by the city posted a rise of 17
percent in the first five months this year. The actually unitized
capital increased 27 percent in the period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of investors, such as the Japanese Isuzu
Motors and Thai Chia Tai Group, added investments in their
existing ventures in the city.
</P>
<P>
Pu Haiqing, newly elected mayor of the city, said that the
city, historically an important industrial and commercial hub,
will continue efforts to turn it into a trade, financial and
information center, a transport and telecom hub, and a high-tech
industrial base.
</P>
<P>
Local economists hoped that the Three Gorges Project, China's
largest hydropower project, and development at reservoir areas
will boost the adjustment of Chongqing's social and economic
structure.
</P>
<P>
Also, the industrial belt to emerge in the city will become
another economic powerhouse for China's sustained economic growth
in the coming new century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
