<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader on Sino-German Ties, Human Rights (Part 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference today outlined China's policies on Sino-German
relations, human rights and Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
When asked about China's attitude on human rights and
legislative accomplishments, Li pointed out that many Western
people failed to understand the real situation of China's human
rights -- which have been purposely distorted by some people.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader epitomized China's three serious and
consistent positions on human rights.
</P>
<P>
First, the universally accepted principles on human rights
deserved respect and should be applied by all members of the
international community.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of China, since its establishment in 1921,
had been devoting itself to achieving and protecting all basic
rights of the Chinese people, and it had been steadfastly
struggling for their political democracy and economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
China, a member of the United Nations Human Rights Commission
had actively participated in all U.N. activities on human rights,
including the drafting and formulating of a series of human rights
documents.
</P>
<P>
China had signed 17 international conventions on human rights
and was poised to ratify the International Convention on Economic,
Social and Cultural Rights by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Li noted, the universal principles of human rights
must be combined with the particular situations of different
countries.
</P>
<P>
Due to the differences in historical background, cultural
traditions and levels of economic development, countries differ in
both content and form, means and measures in implementing the
universal principles of human rights, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader stressed that even the most common principle
acknowledged by all peoples around the world may not do if
divorced from real situations.
</P>
<P>
He gave the example of China's birth control policy. While
giving birth to babies, and deciding how many basic rights there
are for a woman, the future of China, a country with a population
of 1.2 billion, would be unthinkable without family planning.
</P>
<P>
With China's population keeping on doubling, the world as a
whole would become unimaginable, he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Li said, China upholds that the implementation of
the universal principles of human rights must proceed with
reality, must be in the interests of the majority, must follow
order and advance step by step, and great attention must be paid
to its objective effects.
</P>
<P>
"Chanting beautiful words or simply copying the policies of
other countries is impossible for achieving any success, and may
bring even worse consequences," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The third point Li stressed is that the implementation of the
universal principles of human rights is a developing course which
never ends, since the principles themselves develop as economies
and social lives develop.
</P>
<P>
The seemingly perfect principles yesterday are far from perfect
today, while today's perfect principles may leave a large room for
improvement tomorrow, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Implementing human rights principles is a course to ever
pursue, because it is forever changing and forever developing. In
this way, the basic rights of human beings are promoted to a
higher stage, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed out that all countries in the world are on this
course, though their stages are different.
</P>
<P>
No matter what stage a country was at, it had the
responsibility to enhance the level of human rights its people
enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that different countries should join hands in
promoting the development of human rights causes through equal
dialogue and communication.
</P>
<P>
Li was critical of certain people who were overconfident about
their countries' human rights conditions, and made unwarranted
charges against other countries, especially developing ones.
</P>
<P>
"This will bring nothing good to the implementation of the
universal principles of human rights," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Sound jurisdiction is necessary to better protect human rights,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted the late Chinese leader, Deng Xiaoping, as saying
that legality must be strengthened so as to guarantee people's
democracy.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that after the reform and opening up, China had done a
lot of work in perfecting socialist legality by introducing a
series of important laws and strengthening law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, China believes that the level of human
rights a country's people enjoy depends on the development of the
country's economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
Prosperity, democracy and civilization were the three goals
China had set for its comprehensive development.
</P>
<P>
China is making efforts to enhance the level of its people's
human rights along with the enhancement of the country's economy
and society as a whole, Li said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
