<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italians Driving Slower But Ignoring Seatbelt Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Italians are driving their cars more
slowly, but most of them still ignore laws requiring them to wear
seatbelts, according to the results of an international study
published here today.
</P>
<P>
The study says that almost nobody wears their seatbelts in town
and very few on the motorways.
</P>
<P>
The second study carried out under the Social attitudes on road
traffic risks in Europe (Sartre-2)study, said the Italian attitude
could be summed up: "Better a good luck charm than a seatbelt."
</P>
<P>
Researcher Pierangelo Sardi said that observance of the
seatbelt laws could dramatically reduce the current accident toll
on the roads; 9,000 deaths annually, 800,000 people treated in
casualty departments, 170,000 admitted to hospitals, 25,000
seriously disabled.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the country is estimated to be more than 50,000
billion lire (about 30 billion U.S. dollars) in the first half of
the year, according to Franco Taggi of the Higher Institute of
Health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Enterprises Pursuing Sustained Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Rural enterprises in this port
city of north China have made remarkable progress in pursuing
sustained development while paying close attention to
environmental protection and energy saving.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the city has so far set up more
than 10,000 rural enterprises, which turn out 45 percent of the
city's total industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
They have built 396 pollution treatment projects over the past
three years by investing 33.68 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Since the introduction of an energy-saving technology across
the city, the rural brick and tile production enterprises here
have saved, on average, 160,000 tons of coal.
</P>
<P>
To achieve better results in environmental protection and
reduce pollution, the municipal government has urged all towns and
villages to build industrial parks to house rural enterprises, so
that centralized power, heat and water supply systems can be
built. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong, Yunnan Gain from Each Other through Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- South China's prosperous Guangdong
Province signed 38 agreements Wednesday with Yunnan Province in
Southwest China to expand economic ties between them.
</P>
<P>
Insufficient raw materials and energy sources prevent Guangdong
from growing as fast as it could. Yunnan needs more investments to
develop its rich natural resources.
</P>
<P>
The agreements, worth 1.37 billion yuan (165 million US
dollars), involve finance, energy development, sugar processing,
food stuffs, textiles, light industry, agriculture and forestry,
science and technology, medicine, aquatic products and trade.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the projects require investments of more than 10 million
yuan (1.2 million US dollars) each. Two involve investments of
more than 100 million yuan (12.1 million US Dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Chaozhou Jinman Group of Guangdong Province signed a contract
with Yunnan Yuxi city to invest 500 million yuan to raise eels in
Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
And Guangdong Qiancheng Co signed an agreement with a firm in
Yunnan's Qujing city to develop a town gas project which needs 250
million yuan (30 million dollars) to be completed.
</P>
<P>
A Guangdong Province economic commission official said the
economies of Guangdong and Yunnan are strongly supplementary.
</P>
<P>
"The big southwest Chinese market and the potential southeast
Asian opportunities attract Guangdong manufacturers and traders,
while Yunnan expects Guangdong to help it open more means of
expanding in Hong Kong and Macao and the world market," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has 20 projects worth 10 million yuan (1.2 million US
dollars) each in Yunnan province.
</P>
<P>
Last year, about 500 Guangdong manufacturers sold 600 million
yuan (73 million dollars) worth of products in Yunnan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
