<HEADLINE> Mary Slaney Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- American athletics officials
have suspended Mary Slaney for an alleged positive drug test,
making her ineligible for the national championships beganning in
Indianapolis on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The queen of American running also could be forced to forfeit
her silver medal from the women's 1,500 meters at the March world
indoor championships if further U.S. hearings fail to exonerate
her, according reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Reports said a USA Track and Field (USATF) board had suspended
the U.S. women's distance star on Tuesday night. USATF spokesman
Pete Cava declined comment. Slaney's husband, Richard, said the
couple had not been notified "personally."
</P>
<P>
USATF officials on Tuesday declared Slaney an "eligible
athlete" for the championships after receiving a letter from the
IAAF saying she was suspended and that she was ineligible to
compete either in the United States or internationally until a
U.S. hearing is completed on a disputed doping test.
</P>
<P>
IAAF president Primo Nebiolo 11 days ago banned Slaney and
fellow American athletes Sandra Farmer-Patrick and Stephon Flenoy
until their doping cases were resolved by U.S. officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
