<HEADLINE> Arbitrator Orders Flenoy Be Allowed to Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- An arbitrator has ordered
American 400-meter hurdler Stephon Flenoy be allowed to compete in
the national championships starting in Indianapolis Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Flenoy's attorney Ed Williams said Wednesday: "After a full
day's hearing, the arbitrator ruled that he (Flenoy) did not get a
fair hearing before a USA Track and Field custodial board."
</P>
<P>
"He ordered that USA Track and Field reinstate him in the
competition."
</P>
<P>
Flenoy had been suspended by U.S. officials after a doping test
revealed he had a testosterone to epitestosterone ratio higher
than 6-to-1 in violation of IAAF rules. Because of the suspension
he had been declared ineligible for the U.S. championships.
</P>
