<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Genta Hawkins Holmes, the new U.S. ambassador to Australia,
flagged yesterday a fresh era of U.S.-Australian relations with
the focus shifting from security concerns towards global warming,
human rights and international crime. In her first big bilateral
policy statement ahead of Prime Minister John Howard's U.S. visit
later this month, she warned Australia it had to compromise on
greenhouse gas emissions and criticized the country's use of
hydrocarbons.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The New South Wales Chamber of Commerce has issued the most
dire warning yet from business of the impact on trade of the
domestic race debate and has challenged Prime Minister John Howard
to "stop being concerned about losing the votes of Hanson
supporters and concentrate on the implications".
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- A state government department authorized the use of young
children from a Victorian orphanage in a post-war experiment
involving trials of a whopping cough vaccine on animals. The
newspaper reported earlier this week hundreds of orphaned children
have been used in experiments during 1945 and 1970 with adult dose
of vaccines or vaccine on animals.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australian companies risk missing lucrative opportunities in
Japan because they are clinging to outdated ideas that the market
is too difficult to penetrate, a new Department of Foreign Affairs
and Trade study has warned.  
</P>
