<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Cautiously Welcomes UN Arrears Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (xinhua) -- The White House today
cautiously welcomed the agreement reached late Tuesday on how to
pay the U.S. arrears to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Jesse Helms of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
a Republican critic of the U.N., reached a deal with the Democrats
to pay off most of the more than 1 billion U.S. dollars arrears to
the U.N.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said, "It's good that we get
a commitment to move forward on the payment of the arrears." But
he added there are "a lot of details still left to be ironed out."
</P>
<P>
Also State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns responded to the
progress cautiously.
</P>
<P>
"There is no deal yet. There has been a major step forward in
the negotiations," Burns added.
</P>
<P>
"I should caution that much more work remains to be done on
this particular piece of legislation before we can declare...
victory," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the U.S. will pay 819 million U.S. dollars it
owes to the U.N. only after the U.N. takes significant steps in
reforms, including reducing its budgets and cutting the U.S. share
of the U.N. fees, officials were quoted by local reports as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, future payment of the U.S. dues to the U.N. will be
made on a variety of conditions raised by Chairman Jesse Helms of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
Helms proposed that if diplomats in New York did not pay their
parking tickets, the U.S. would cut its aid to their countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, under the agreement, the U.S.'s annual dues share
at the U.N. will drop from 25 percent to 20 percent by the year of
2000.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that the conditions will be strongly protested
at the U.N., where the U.S. is already viewed as playing hegemony
by many countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement still requires approval by Congress and the
signature of President Bill Clinton and will be made public when
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee meets Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations with the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
have not resolved all issues, including the timetable for paying
back the debt.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, the U.S. representative at the U.N., said
Tuesday evening that the administration remained concerned about
some of the conditions in the agreement, but considered it "a
major step forward."
</P>
<P>
"We have a chance to get a real bipartisan package that will be
acceptable at the United Nations," Richardson told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
