<HEADLINE> New Cabinet Formed in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien today announced the membership of the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, Veteran MP Herbert Gray has been
appointed deputy prime minister; Lloyd Axworthy continues as
minister of foreign affairs; Sheila Copps retains the position of
minister of Canadian heritage; Paul Martin continues as minister
of finance; Sergio Marchi is appointed minister for international
trade; Diane Marleau becomes minister for international
cooperation and minister responsible for Francophonie; Arthur
Eggleton has been appointed minister of national defense.
</P>
<P>
With today's appointments, the number of cabinet ministers will
increase by three to 27 ministers and the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
After announcing the appointments, the prime minister said,
"Our job now is to build on the accomplishments of our first
mandate and work with Canadians to meet the challenges that face
our country: to continue to build a strong economy that creates
jobs and opportunity; to complete the task of balancing the budget
and putting Canada's finances on a sound and sustainable footing;
to modernize and expand our health care system; and to provide for
the well-being of our children."
</P>
<P>
Canada's ruling Liberal Party won 154 seats of a total of 301
in the election held on June 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
