<HEADLINE> Kohl, Kok Meet to Prepare for EU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl met
with Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok today, discussing the upcoming
European Union (EU) summit meeting in Amsterdam on June 16-17.
</P>
<P>
Kok said he was confident that the Amsterdam summit would be a
success which would push the EU a great step forward. He added
that this was also the wish of the French government.
</P>
<P>
Kok arrived in Bonn from a visit to Paris today. Paris Tuesday
said it needed more time to consider a currency union stability
pact necessary for the 1999 start-up of the single European
currency, the euro, and asked for the extension of the pact to
address its job concerns.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel told
parliament that Bonn, which had been opposing the EU jobs pact,
now approved it to meet the demand of France, and said that France
would sign the stability pact.
</P>
<P>
The currency union stability pact and the reformed Maastricht
II Treaty are supposed to be signed at the Amsterdam summit.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Kok, kohl praised the preparation work of
the Dutch government for the EU summit, adding that Germany would
do its best to make the meeting a success.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands currently holds the rotating presidency of the
EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
