<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Dollar Weakens Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a nine-month
low against the Japanese yen today after Japan reported a sharply
higher trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
It was the fifth straight day the dollar declined against the
yen, and the selling helped pull the U.S. currency lower in most
other foreign-exchange dealings.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell to an intraday low of 110.52 yen, the weakest
since September 11, before recovering somewhat to settle in New
York at 111.20 yen, down from 112.25 yen Tuesday. The dollar cost
1.7160 marks, down from 1.7185. The pound cost 1.6377 U.S.
dollars, down from 1.6385 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar has so far retreated more than five yen or 4.3
percent in a week and fallen more than 16 yen or 12.8 percent from
its four-year high of 127.27 yen reached on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Finance Ministry reported that Japan's April surplus
rose 92.7 percent to 1.1 trillion yen in April compared with the
year earlier. It was the second straight monthly increase.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's weakness against European currencies partly
reflected the continuing uncertainty over the future of the euro.
</P>
<P>
Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with late Tuesday:
1.4375 Swiss francs, down from 1.4417; 5.8035 French francs, down
from 5.8060; 1,694.50 Italian lire, down from 1,696.00; 1.3867
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3873. 
</P>
</TEXT>
