<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers Commit to Sustainable Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TORONTO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Environment Ministerial
Meeting of Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) concluded here
today, with commitments of more efforts into the region's
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The ministers "commit to sustainable development as a
fundamental objective to achieve human prosperity and a healthy
environment," said a joint statement released at the meeting's
end.
</P>
<P>
They challenged "all orders of government, the private sector,
local communities, and individuals to join us in transforming
sustainable development principles into meaningful practices and
visible results," the document said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was supposed to "find better ways of putting the
principle of sustainable development into practice," according to
Sergio Marchi, who chaired the opening of the meeting and has been
transferred from the environment to international trade portfolio
in today's cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, the discussions were focused
mainly on items of sustainable cities, sustainability of the
marine environment, cleaner production and environmentally
sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
"Sustainable development in the APEC region is fundamentally
linked to the sustainability of cities," the document noted.
</P>
<P>
Cities in APEC economies are growing at a rapid pace. Ten of
the 15 largest cities in the world are now in APEC economies. By
2015, the proportion of APEC populations living in cities is
expected to grow to 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
"All aspects of urban planning and development must therefore
be people-centered and take into account environmental protection
and economic and social considerations," it stressed.
</P>
<P>
On sustainability of the marine environment, the ministers
"commit to take action to protect this collective resources, as we
pursue our commitment to make dramatic progress toward clean
oceans and seas in the APEC region."
</P>
<P>
The meeting endorsed the Strategy for Sustainability of the
Marine Environment in the APEC region and commended it to APEC
economic leaders when they meet in Vancouver in November.
</P>
<P>
As of cleaner production, the document said that new investment
in the region "offers an opportunity to incorporate flexible and
cost-effective environmental management techniques to achieve more
sustainable industrial development."
</P>
<P>
"APEC will promote cleaner production in industrial sectors, by
identifying and expanding best practices and establishing a
cooperative agenda for technology diffusion," it said.
</P>
<P>
The document also called for improved coordination to link and
integrate the many sustainable development initiatives with APEC.
</P>
<P>
APEC is made up of Australia, Brunei Darussalam, Canada, Chile,
the People's Republic of China, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua New
Guinea, the Republic of the Philippines, Singapore, Chinese
Taipei, Thailand and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ministers and their representatives from all 18 APEC economies
participated in the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Iraqi Weapons Inspector Asks for Council's Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. weapons inspectors in
Iraq asked the Security Council for support today after Iraq
forced them to halt arms inspection last week by interfering with
four helicopter flights.
</P>
<P>
The chief inspector, Rolf Ekeus, briefed the Security Council
on reports that Iraqi officers manhandled U.N. personnel, grabbed
pilot controls, threatened to shut off a fuel pump and endangered
the lives of helicopter crew members.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the council
will likely issue a formal statement Thursday urging Iraq to
respect the safety of U.N. inspectors. The inspectors are in Iraq
to determine whether Baghdad has complied with U.N. orders to
destroy its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
On the complaints of the U.N. weapons inspectors, Iraq said the
incidents occurred when the U.N. teams were attempting to fly over
sensitive areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
