<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Scientists Search for Nuclear Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Sitting amidst sophisticated
detectors under a tall chimney, Indian atomic scientists have made
a fascinating discovery of possible nuclear reactions taking place
during lightning discharges, Press Trust of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
A team from India's Bhabha Atomic Research Center (BARC) based
in Bombay (Mumbai) observed bursts of neutrons -- uncharged
particles present in the nucleus of an atom -- during lightning
discharges.
</P>
<P>
Dome bursts contained as many as a billion neutrons. Such
neutrons are usually released in nuclear reactions.
</P>
<P>
Lightning discharges in the air are already known to carry
currents of several tens of kilo amperes, high energy X-rays and
gamma rays.
</P>
<P>
The scientists say they have detected neutrons indicating the
occurrence of nuclear reactions during lightning.
</P>
<P>
Their findings were reported in the latest issue of the Indian
Journal of Radio and Space Physics.
</P>
<P>
The neutrons are probably produced when hydrogen ions (natural
hydrogen is present in the form of water) collide with air
(containing nitrogen and oxygen) or with trees (containing carbon)
or even lightning arresters (containing copper), the scientists
say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
