<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Finds Hard to Knit Local Service Net </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. has made scant
progress in entering local service network a year after it
promised to do so, according to a report by the Wall Street
Journal today.
</P>
<P>
The company vowed to spend billions of U.S. dollars to erect
rival networks that would capture in just four years one-third of
the local phone business which generates 100 billion U.S. dollars
a year.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T is now deeply involved in merger discussions with Bell
giant SBC Communications Corp., a transaction that would be valued
at more than 50 billion U.S. dollars. Such a combination would let
AT&AMP;T forgo offering local service in the two big regions SBC
covers and add its power for pushing into other regions, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T planners now realize it could take as much as 30 billion
to crack the nation's local markets by building networks across
the country.
</P>
<P>
The company chairman Robert Allen was quoted as saying that
resistance by the Bells to open their local markets fully to
competitors is an even bigger constraint than capital.
</P>
<P>
But the company worked out an aggressive plan to attack on all
fronts rather than creep into individual markets one at a time.
Last year, AT&AMP;T began building the first of 52 fiber-optic "rings"
for carrying long-distance traffic. These rings will eventually
be linked to more than 100 smaller local rings offering local
service in communities nationwide, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T's own internal studies show it could lose up to one-third
of its long-distance business to the Bells within 18 months to two
years after they enter the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
