<HEADLINE> Congolese President Orders Troops to Cease Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Congo Republic President Pascal
Lissouba today ordered his troops to start a ceasefire immediately
in their engagement with the militiamen supporting former
President Denis Sassou-N'Guesso, according to reports reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
"I order a ceasefire from this instant as I address to you, to
give a chance to the national mediation already under way and to
an international mediation which will follow," said Lissouba in a
broadcast speech on the national radio in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government soldiers were originally carrying
out a task to restore law and order, but that turned out to be a
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out last Thursday after government troops
surrounded the residence of Sassou N'Guesso and tried to disarm
the private force owned by the latter.
</P>
<P>
Sassou-N'Guesso also said today that he supports a ceasefire in
Brazzaville if the government troops stop bombarding with heavy
artilleries the districts under the control of his men.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the RTL, a private broadcasting network
based in Luxembourg, Sassou-N'Guesso asked "the aggressor to stop
the bombardments of the popular districts which we control," as a
precondition for a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The mayor of Brazzaville Bernard Kolelas, who is also president
of the national committee of mediation and the head of a third
force of Congo, had earlier asked Lissouba to order a ceasefire
"in a first step," before Sassou N'Guesso asked his men to stop
shooting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
