<HEADLINE> Foreign News Agencies Free to Channel News in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign news agencies and
other information providers would soon be free to channel news
and information direct to subscribers in Malaysia, bypassing the
national news agency, according to a government decision today.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government today decided to withdraw the
exclusive rights granted to the National News Agency Bernama for
the distribution of foreign news in the country in a move to allow
a free flow of information, Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat
announced here.
</P>
<P>
The minister told reporters that steps were being taken to
amend the Bernama Act to remove the rights now enjoyed by the
national news agency.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed said his ministry was working with the
Attorney-General's Chambers to draft the amendments which he hoped
to bring to the cabinet as soon as possible before being tabled in
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing Act, the flow of foreign news into Malaysia
is required to go through Bernama, not for the purpose of
censorship but for providing the national news agency with an
additional source of revenue.
</P>
<P>
The rights bring Bernama about 8 million Ringgit (about 3.2
million US dollars) in royalty annually, or 20 percent of its
gross income of about 40 million Ringgit (about 16 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
"We want to ensure a free flow of information. If Bernama
suffers a loss due to this move, we will make up for it through
other means," the minister said, adding Bernama could be given
other business opportunities with several proposals to be
presented to the cabinet to compensate Bernama for its loss of
revenue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
