<HEADLINE> U.S. May Pay U.N. Dues with Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (xinhua) -- The Clinton Administration
reached agreement late Tuesday with the Republican-dominated
Senate on a plan to pay 819 million U.S. dollars arrears to the
United Nations with conditions.
</P>
<P>
The payment would come only after the U.N. took significant
steps in reforms, including reducing its budgets and cutting U.S.
share of the U.N. fees, officials were quoted by local reports as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, future payment of the U.S. dues to the U.N. would be
made on a variety of conditions raised by Chairman Jesse Helms of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
Helms proposed that if diplomats in New York do not pay their
parking tickets, the U.S. would cut its aid to their countries.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that the conditions would be strongly
protested at the U.N., where the U.S. is already viewed as playing
hegemony by many member countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement still requires approval by Congress and the
signature of President Bill Clinton and will be made public when
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee meet on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, the U.S. representative at the U.N., said
Tuesday evening that the Administration remained concerned about
some of the conditions in the agreement, but considered it "a
major step forward."
</P>
<P>
"We have a chance to get a real bipartisan package that will be
acceptable at the United Nations," Richardson told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
