<HEADLINE> Blair, Chirac to Exchange Views on EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Prime Minister Tony
Blair, who is to pay a brief visit to France later today, would
not persuade French President Jacques Chirac into delaying the
European Monetary Union (EMU) project, according to British
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Blair will hold talks with President Chirac in Paris this
evening as part of a round of diplomacy ahead of the European
Union (EU) summit to be held in Amsterdam next week, British
officials said.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that Blair, well aware of the political
difficulties in Paris on the single European currency, would not
take counterproductive and hostile stance on the EMU issue, saying
"He's not going to rain on their parade."
</P>
<P>
However, the British Prime Minister is expected to stress the
need to avoid fudging the economic convergence criteria for the
single currency, they said.
</P>
<P>
On Britain's EMU membership, Blair has said that it is very
unlikely that Britain will be among the first wave of EU countries
to join the EMU, but Britain is well placed to influence the
project because it has not ruled out joining later.
</P>
<P>
"The option is genuinely open that we will join at some
stage," a senior aide for Blair said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
