<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister to Attend Hong Kong Handover Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
announced today he would go to Hong Kong himself to attend the
ceremony marking the handover of Hong Kong to China on June 30.
</P>
<P>
While speaking in parliament, Blair said he thought the
continued concern of Britain over Hong Kong was important and "I
will be attending the ceremony myself," ending weeks of
speculation whether the British prime minister would attend the
historic ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Prince of Wales Charles and British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook will also go to Hong Kong for the grand ceremony which would
be attended by more than 4,000 dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
In the Chinese side, President Jiang Zemin will head the
Chinese delegation to attend the joint Sino-British ceremony
marking the transfer of power of Hong Kong to China after more
than 150 years of British rule.  
</P>
