<HEADLINE> Kinkel: Bonn Approves Jobs Deal for Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
told parliament today that Bonn would approve a jobs pact demanded
by France and that the currency union would start as planned in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Bonn's approval of the European Union (EU) jobs deal which it
had been opposed was in concession to Paris, which Tuesday voiced
attempt to delay a currency union stability pact needed for the
planned launch from 1999 of the single European currency, the
euro.
</P>
<P>
Paris said that it still needed more time to consider the pact,
which, agreed last December and supposed to be signed at the
upcoming EU summit in Amsterdam on June 16-17, would impose huge
fines on single currency states failing to meet the budget deficit
criteria.
</P>
<P>
Paris later asked for the extension of the pact to address its
job concerns and French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said he
thought the pact would be signed at Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
In his speech on the EU Amsterdam summit which is due to
conclude constitutional reforms known as Maastricht II, Kinkel
stressed that job creation remained primarily the task of
individual EU member states and that Bonn would reject expensive
state employment programs.
</P>
<P>
France would sign the currency union stability pact, he
assured, and warned of a possible lack of political will to renew
efforts to introduce euro if the single currency was delayed.
</P>
<P>
It was also very likely that the reformed Maastricht II Treaty
would leave out many of Germany's proposals such as calls for
common asylum, visa, refugee and immigration policy, and an end to
the national veto right of single EU state and more majority
voting.
</P>
<P>
"None of the members states -- ourselves included -- will be
able to force through their maximum demands," said Kinkel, who
stressed that small steps would be taken before the emerging of a
united Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
