<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Large Scale Manufacturing Witnesses Lowest Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has experienced the
lowest growth rate of minus 1.4 percent in large scale
manufacturing during the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz made the remarks today when
launching the annual "Economic Survey" which was released before
the announcement of the federal fiscal budget.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who will present the budget for the 1997-1998 fiscal year
on Friday, said at a a crowded press conference that the
pre-budget document was based on the estimates of the first nine
months of the 1996-97 fiscal year ending June 30.
</P>
<P>
The survey underlined the dismal performance of economic
indicators, with the hope to revive the economy through the
economic reforms program of the government lead by Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
For the current fiscal year, the survey draws a bleak picture
of the economic performance with sharp decline in growth, steep
rise in inflation and significantly widening trade and fiscal
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Giving details of the gloomy performance in the GDP (gross
domestic product) growth, the finance minister said it was 3.1
percent in the current fiscal year as against the target of 6.3
percent. Last year the GDP growth was recorded at 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the large scale manufacturing sector received major
setbacks recording a negative 1.4 percent growth which was
unprecedented in the country's economic history, the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the Economic Survey, he said that the decline in
industrial growth led to a decline in per capita income and a rise
in inflation.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out the sky-rocketing inflation as one of the major
areas which witnessed the worst performance during the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1997 inflation remained at an average of 12
percent, showing a 50 percent increase in prices, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
