<HEADLINE> Egyptian Leaders Review Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's key policy-makers met today
to take stock of the latest Mideast development and the current
efforts to revive the peace process, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak called the meeting to make a complete
evaluation of the Mideast peace drive, Moussa said after the
meeting which was also attended by Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri and Presidential Political Advisor Osama el-Baz.
</P>
<P>
"The gap remains wide in place as the Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators are geared up for their second meeting in three
months," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt brokered a first meeting in three months between experts
of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and Israel here Sunday
in a bid to break the deadlock caused by the Israeli move to build
new settlement for Jews in disputed Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
No breakthrough was made at Sunday's meeting, but the
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators agreed to meet in Israel
Thursday again, with the participation of Egypt, to narrow the
wide gap dividing them.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Baz will meet with PNA President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to make preparation for
tripartite talks which "cannot be held in a vacuum."
</P>
<P>
"The important issue (about holding another expert meeting) is
making progress. But the gap remains wide and the issue of
settlements still sticks out," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian top diplomat also expressed regret over
Netanyahu's recent statements that Israel will not withdraw to the
pre-1967 borders, that Jerusalem will remain the united capital of
Israel and that Israel will never give up East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Such statements make the peace process very difficult, and if
this is the case, all ongoing efforts are bound to fail," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said contacts were going on in all directions, but he
stressed "we should concentrate on contacts that have already been
made."
</P>
<P>
Without elaborating, he said "we should wait for the results of
tomorrow's meeting."
</P>
<P>
Arafat has been pressing Israel for a three to six months halt
in settlement building to allow talks on a final resolution of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict to restart.
</P>
<P>
However, the controversy over the Jewish settlement expansion
policy seemed to be deepening Tuesday as Netanyahu rejected the
key Palestinian demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
