<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pakistan's Export Target Unlikely to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's export target for the
current fiscal year is unlikely to be achieved because of the poor
performance of the pivotal textile sector.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings for the 1996-97 fiscal year were projected at
10 billion US dollars as against 8.71 billion dollars achieved in
the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Economic Survey for 1996-97 released here
today, the export receipts during the 10 month period (July
1996-April 1997) were 6.812 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said here today that with export earnings of
only two months uncalculated, the export target for the current
fiscal year ending June 30 was apparently beyond achievement.
</P>
<P>
The sources attributed the lower exports to restricted
performance of the textile sector which accounts for more than 60
percent of the country's total export items.
</P>
<P>
Of 432 textile units in Pakistan, 49 composite units and 120
other units have been either closed down due to financial
constraints or are heading towards that end, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Due to shortage of raw materials and increased manufacturing
costs, the local cloth production has been substantially reduced.
</P>
<P>
It is for this reason that Pakistan's export, which mostly
depends upon the overall performance of the textile sector, has
been hit hard during the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Cotton-related exports constitute over 60 percent of Pakistan's
total exports, and earn on an average six to seven billion dollars
in foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
However, during the 11 months of the current fiscal year, the
textile sector exports remained below the four billion dollar
mark.
</P>
<P>
Textile exports during the last four years had shown a
considerable decline. In 1991-92, textile exports were 65 percent
of total exports with earnings of 5.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1992-93 and 1993-94, the percentage of textile exports
dropped to 52 percent, as the overall exports of the country
declined. The foreign exchange earnings from textile exports were
4.8 billion dollars in 1994-95 and slightly over 4.9 billion
dollars in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
However, in the current fiscal year, textile exports as well as
overall exports failed to show any improvement despite a bit
relaxed cotton availability situation and huge demand in the
international market.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that under the prevailing conditions there is
little chance of improvement in the overall export figures for the
outgoing fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The export earnings for the whole year is expected to stay
around a mere eight billion dollars. The textile sector exports is
to remain around 4.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, unconventional exports, to which much importance was
attached by the former government, did not show expected
performance.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe that lack of financial assistance to
exporters and rapid changes in the government policies and
restrictions by importing countries are the main reasons for the
poor performance of the unconventional export sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
