<HEADLINE> Germany's Preussag Confirms Interest in Taking over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Hanover-based German energy and
industrial conglomerate Preussag AG today for the first time
openly confirmed its interest in a friendly takeover of the
Hamburg shipping and tourism firm Hapag-Lloyd, saying relevant
talks were already underway.
</P>
<P>
Preussag said that the talks now focused on how to maintain and
expand Hapag-Lloyd in its current structure, stressing in a
statement: "Any speculation that Hapag-Lloyd would be broken up is
devoid of any basis."
</P>
<P>
It added that takeover of the majority will come only after the
agreement of Hapag-Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
Hapag-Lloyd has about 9,000 employees, with reported revenues
in 1996 at 4.5 billion marks (over 2.6 billion US dollars), 53
percent of which in shipping. The firm also has its own tourism
airline, travel firm and cruise shipping line.
</P>
<P>
Preussag has about 66,300 employees and reported its revenues
last year at 25 billion marks (14.6 billion dollars). Its
VTG-Lenkering subsidiary is specialized in various rail, river and
ocean shipping activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
