<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Invites Cypriot Community Leaders to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Cyprus' major Greek and
Turkish communities today received U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's invitations to participate in direct negotiations on the
Cyprus problem next month.
</P>
<P>
The invitations were handed over to Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash by U.N. Resident
Representative Gustave Feissel.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after his meeting with Clerides, Feissel
said the talks will begin on July 9, and will take place somewhere
near New York.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official refrained from giving any details on the
content of the invitation, saying that both sides should come to
talks in a spirit of good-will and be ready to make their
contribution to an overall settlement.
</P>
<P>
Feissel said he is not aware if Annan has extended invitations
to foreign government envoys concerned in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports have said that representatives of Britain,
France, Russia and the U.S. will be present at the direct
negotiations between the two Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. invitations were issued after the three-month U.N.-led
proximity talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides in an
effort to create right atmosphere for the direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Both Clerides and Denktash have responded positively to the
U.N. proposed direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in Cyprus has remained deadlocked since
October, 1994, when Clerides and Denktash held two rounds of
informal meetings in Nicosia under the U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of
the island in the wake of a short-lived coup seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
