<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Performance of Economy Below Expectation: Pak Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The performance of Pakistan's
economy during the 1996-97 fiscal year was below expectation with
a decline in GDP growth and only a nominal increase in per capita
income, an economic report said today.
</P>
<P>
Based on data for the first 9 months of the year, the country's
GDP (gross domestic product) has been tentatively estimated at 3.1
percent in 1996-97, which shows a decline from the growth of 4.6
percent during 1995-1996, according to the "Economic Survey"
released here today.
</P>
<P>
The annually pre-budget report said that the agricultural
sector, the largest sector of the national economy, has shown a
nominal growth of 0.7 percent against last year's high growth of
5.27 percent, which essentially resulted from a decline of 4.51
percent in the major crops sub-sector.
</P>
<P>
The report said that monetary expansion remained well within
targets but the deficits in the budget and balance of payments
were very much higher than planned.
</P>
<P>
Excluding raw cotton the exports grew by 9 percent but overall
exports remained static while imports grew at a rate of 1.5
percent during the first 10 months of the year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic prices got shocks from domestic output set-backs and
policy adjustments in the utilities' pricing and the increase in
support prices of agricultural crops, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the manufacturing sector, small scale manufactures have
grown by 8.4 percent while the large manufactures registered a
decline of 1.4 percent, meaning that the growth of manufacturing
as a whole is estimated at 1.8 percent in 1996-97 compared with
4.4 percent last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Total investment has gone up by 12.7 percent and stood at 18.4
percent of GNP (gross national product), the report said, adding
private investment has increased by 15.6 percent, national savings
increased by 12.2 percent and foreign savings by 13.4 percent, it
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
