<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Welcomes U.N. Invitation for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
welcomed invitation by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
President Glafcos Clerides for a face-to-face talks between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders in July.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides said that "the Cypriot government is
satisfied with the invitation" which was handed over to Clerides
today by the U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks will be held somewhere near New York
between July 9 and 13.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Annan will chair the talks in the beginning
and then his Special Representative for Cyprus, Diego Cordovez
will take over. During the talks, Annan will be available for the
two interlocutors when needed, he added.
</P>
<P>
"This is the beginning of a new effort toward finding a Cyprus
solution and it will last as long as necessary," Christofides
said, noting that more meetings will follow.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. source here, the direct negotiations will
be preceded by an informal dinner at the residence of the U.N.
secretary-general in New York on July 8.
</P>
<P>
"The idea is to give an opportunity to both (Clerides and
Denktash) to warm up," the source said.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash had two
U.N.-sponsored informal meetings in Nicosia in October, 1994,
which ended in a deadlock. The two men have not met since.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
