<HEADLINE> Santer Calls for EU Leaders to Make Amsterdam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- European Commission President
Jacques Santer on Wednesday urged European Union member nations to
make improvements to approve plans on EU reforms at a summit in
Amsterdam next week.
</P>
<P>
"If we can make improvements let's do that, but let's not
jeopardize the project by last minute special pleading which may
undermine the balance we have arrived at," Santer told the
European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking two days after France's new Socialist
government threw the EU into turmoil by telling its partners it
wanted time to study an already agreed deal, the stability pact,
designed to keep budget deficits tight after the single currency
is introduced on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The pact was supposed to be ratified by EU leaders in Amsterdam
on June 16-17 as they are to approve internal EU reforms in a
revised treaty designed to prepare the 15-member bloc for its
ambitious expansion eastward.
</P>
<P>
EU member states are trying hard to find a compromise by
including additional elements on employment policy in the
so-called Maastricht II treaty, to be agreed in Amsterdam, to meet
France's concerns.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van Mierlo, whose country currently
holds the EU presidency, told the EU assembly that he was
confident that France would find a solution to allow the stability
pact to be approved at Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
Santer said that there was no question of renegotiating the
stability pact which has been agreed by EU leaders in Dublin in
December.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Amsterdam summit should not backtrack on
provisional agreements to give the EU more powers to act on issues
which concerned its citizens, especially unemployment and social
issues, free movements of people around the Union, health and
consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
He urged EU governments to reach a deal next week which would
reconcile efforts to create a Union more integrated with the needs
of its citizens, to give the EU a strong united voice in world
affairs backed by military capacity and to make its own
institutions more efficient and democratic in time for
enlargement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
