<HEADLINE> Pak Price Situation Remains Under Stress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- During July-April 1996-97,
Pakistan's Consumer Price Indicator (CPI) recorded an increase of
13.03 percent, Wholesale Price Index 12.11 percent and Sensitive
Price Indicator 13.32 percent, said an economic report released
here today.
</P>
<P>
Giving account of the prices, the Economic Survey for 1996-97
said that it came under greater pressures in the 1990s, when
inflation rate on average remained in double digit.
</P>
<P>
Price situation remained under stress during the current fiscal
year, the survey said. A host of cost push and supply-side factors
were on the forefront to pressurize domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of Pakistani currency of rupee, increases in
utility tariffs, revision in sales tax and excise duty raised the
cost of production while depressed domestic production constrained
the availability in the local market, it said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, support prices of agriculture crops which were
raised to protect the interests of farmers had an inflationary
impact, the survey said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
