<HEADLINE> Jordan Willing to Expand Economic Cooperation With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 11 (Xinhua) - Jordan today expressed willingness to
expand economic cooperation with Qatar, a Gulf nation that severed
ties with the kingdom during the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The integration of economic construction with human dimension
should be emphasized and the Jordanian-Qatari cooperation is one
aspect of the integration, said Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan while
meeting a Qatari businessmen delegation here today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation headed by Board Chairman of Qatar's National
Hotels Company Sheikh Abdullah Ben Ahmad Al Thani, arrived here
yesterday on a 5-day visit to seek investment opportunities in the
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Thani said that Qatar is interested in
setting up joint ventures with Jordan, especially in the tourism
sector.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is one of Jordan's pillar industry. It earned 600
million U.S. dollars a year in the 1980s, some 10 percent of the
kingdom's gross national product.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ensour
briefed the delegation on the government's investment policy and
the strategy to promote the private sector's role in the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
The delegation met Jordanian Minister of Tourism and
Antiquities Akel Beltaji yesterday and will hold further talks
with Jordan's trade and economic representatives in the coming
days.
</P>
<P>
Qatar severed its relations with Jordan after the Gulf Crisis
broke out for Jordan sided with Iraq. When Jordan later distanced
itself away from Iraq to end international isolation, Qatar began
to restore touch in various sectors with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's exports to Qatar reached some 25 million U.S. dollars
in 1996 compared with about 14 million dollars in the previous
year, according to a report of the Amman Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Qatar exported some 8 million U.S. dollars worth of goods to
Jordan in 1996 compared with 9 million dollars in the previous
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
