<HEADLINE> Taliban Retreats from Northern Provincial Capital: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Islamic Taliban militia
were pushed back today by opposing forces from Pul-e-Khomri,
capital of northern Baghlan province, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's offensive was repulsed by forces led by Mansoor
Nadvi, an ally of former military chief Ahmad Masood, said the
Taliban sources in Peshawar, Pakistan's northwestern major city.
</P>
<P>
But the sources claimed that it was a "tactic retreat", adding
that the Taliban were preparing a fresh attack on Pul-e-Khomri,
about 150 kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 to 3,000 Taliban forces led by their "information
minister" Muhammad Muttaqi were now trapped in Pul-e-Khomri. In
the past few days the Islamic militia tried in vain to rescue the
group.
</P>
<P>
Muttaqi's forces became stuck when an enemy-turned-ally
switched allegiances again as the contingent was heading for the
northern capital of Mazar-e-Sharif, leaving them surrounded by
opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban are currently facing an opposition of coalition
allies made up of Masood, ethnic Uzbek general Abdul Malik and the
Shiite religious minority faction Hezb-e-Wahdat in northern
Afghanistan.  
</P>
