<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Raise Import Duties on Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon announced today that import
duties on cars will be raised to protect environment.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at an extraordinary cabinet session
Tuesday night with the aim of "protecting the environment,
reducing the number of vehicles in Lebanon and improving the
country's balance of payment," said Fuad Sinyoura, minister of
state for financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the state-owned Lebanese National News Agency
as saying today that Lebanon is having too many cars, importing
some 75,000 cars annually at a cost of around 800 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are a total of 1.3 million cars in the
country, or a car for every three persons -- a ratio higher than
that in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Sinyoura said the burden of duty increase would fall on buyers
of middle-class and luxury vehicles as the duty on economical
vehicles has not changed.
</P>
<P>
Second-hand cars valued at less than 10,000 U.S. dollars will
not be affected because the minimum duty on them, which is 5
million Lebanese pounds (3,250 dollars), does not change, the
minister said, adding that new cars with a value of 10,000 dollars
or less will have 20 percent duty.
</P>
<P>
More expensive cars, costing between 10,000 U.S. dollars and
32,500 dollars, carry a 50 percent tax, which doubles to 100
percent for cars priced between 32,500 dollars and 65,000
dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The customs duty on luxury cars costing more than 65,000
dollars is set at 200 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sinyoura stressed that the taxes would discourage people from
owning cars and boost public transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey: No Fixed Date for Withdrawal From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish military operations that
began a month ago in northern Iraq will continue until routing
terrorism in the region, Turkish State Minister for Foreign
Affairs Abdullah Gul said here today.
</P>
<P>
Gul, who arrived this morning on a brief visit, made the
statement after handing over a message to Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak from Turkish President Suelyman Demirel on the
fragile situation in northern Iraq and the controversial
Turkish-Israeli military manoeuvers.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the meeting, he defended Turkey's incursion into
northern Iraq as a mission to "protect its territorial integrity
and citizens and fight terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Turkish troops, backed by air power, poured into
northern Iraq on May 14 in a cross-border operation against the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) bases which were used for
raids into southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Gul told reporters that the military operation will end only
after meeting its aim, namely routing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa disputed the point
and said that Iraq should not be left open to any intervention
without considering its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also lamented the failure of Turkey to announce a fixed
date for getting out of the Iraqi territories.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has previously sent a message to Demirel voicing deep
concern over the Turkish military movement in northern Iraq which
has stirred Arab anger and world condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The message from Demirel also dealt with the planned joint
Israeli-Turkish military exercises in the Mediterranean in the
summer, said the Egyptian top diplomat.
</P>
<P>
Moussa confirmed that these manoeuvers have not yet taken
place, but he warned the military coalition between Israel and
Turkey is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
"Such relations could undermine or damage the situation in the
region as well as the Mideast peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This move can escalate tension, especially that its timing
was not suitable," Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
Gul argued that those relations could never harm interests of
countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said consultations and contacts between the two presidents
are continuing in this respect "as we sometimes find an
interpretation which differs from the essence of the
Turkish-Israeli ties."
</P>
<P>
The planned war games that involve Israel, Turkey and the
U.S. in the Mediterranean in the summer have sparked fear in the
Arab world despite Ankara's assurance that they are of a
"humanitarian nature" and not targeted against any Arab country.
</P>
