<HEADLINE> WFP to Launch Emergency Food Relief in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) planned to provide food relief to some 360,000
people living in southern Somalia before the arrival of the main
cereal harvest at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,300 tons of food would be provided for the operation
which needs two million U.S. Dollars to pay transport costs, said
a WFP report issued here today.
</P>
<P>
Rains failed to come at the end of last year, resulting in
record-low production levels for Somalia's 1996-97 dry season.
</P>
<P>
The yield of sorghum, one of the two main cereals cultivated
in the dry season, was 20 percent lower than that of last year
and 80 percent lower than pre-war levels, said the report.
</P>
<P>
As a result, malnutrition, particularly among children, was
increasing at alarming rates. Many families in southwestern
Somalia have already begun migrating to urban areas and feeding
centers in search of food and assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
