<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.S. of Blocking Oil-for-Food Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi newspaper today held the
U.S. responsible for blocking the implementation of the Memorandum
of Understanding (MOU) signed by Iraq and the U.N. a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial published here on Wednesday, Ath-tharwa Daily,
mouthpiece of the ruling Baath Party, said the U.S. shoulders
"moral and legal responsibility for the deaths of Iraqi children
and patients who could have been saved."
</P>
<P>
It is reported that more than 1 million Iraqis died of diseases
and malnutrition since the U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq after
its August 1990 invasion of Kuwait. Most of them are women,
children and the aged.
</P>
<P>
The MOU, known as the oil-for-food deal, allows Iraq to buy 2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over six months to buy food,
medicine and other daily necessities. The deal has been renewed
for another six months from June 7.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq has accused the U.S. of deliberately delaying the
approval of the contracts Iraq signed with foreign companies under
the deal. Such contracts must be approved unanimously by the 15
U.N. Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
As a permanent Security Council member, the U.S. insists that
the U.N. impose tight controls to make sure the supplies are
distributed fairly and not used for military purpose.
</P>
<P>
The daily described the U.S. keenness to implement the MOU and
the "pretentious" humanitarian objectives which the U.S. officials
have been advocating as "mere hypocrisy that aims to absorb the
anti-U.S. pressure" inside and outside the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
It cited as an example the U.S. "unwarranted" interference in
the course of negotiations between Iraq and the U.N. held before
the MOU was concluded.
</P>
<P>
The daily asserted that before signing the MOU, Iraq had took
necessary measures to pave the way for oil contracts while making
preparations for the oil export and import of foodstuff, because
Iraq had expected the U.S.-made obstacles in the way of its
implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
