<DOCNO> XIE19970612.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar's 1997/98 Budget Proposals Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar 1997/98 budget
proposals and development plan were passed today at the House of
Representatives in the town of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, the Zanzibar government
pledged to revamp the economy through increased investments and
improved revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
The government will, during the next financial year, spend
55.4 billion Tanzania Shillings (about 92 million US Dollars),
out of which 42.4 billion T.Shs. will be for recurrent
expenditure while the rest will be for development expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Winding up the debate on the budget proposals which began on
Monday, Finance Minister Amina Salum Ali said that the government
will embark on a massive revenue collection drive to be
spearheaded by the new Zanzibar Revenue Board.
</P>
<P>
She said close supervision would be effected on petroleum
trade and the tourism industry to ensure availability of more
revenue.
</P>
<P>
Ali said the government will promote and closely monitor the
investment sector in addition to putting more emphasis on the
collection of revenue from inland sources and reduce dependence
on customs duty which depended on favourable business trends.
</P>
<P>
The government expects to collect 40.5 billion T.Shs. (about
67 million US Dollars) from various internal sources during
1997/98.
</P>
<P>
She said the government would continue to support development
projects through the injection of funds set aside for the
project. She, however, noted that the zeal shown by the people in
spearheading self-help projects was far above government
resources.
</P>
<P>
Winding up debate on the development plan earlier, the Minister
of State in the President's Office, Ali Juma Shamhuna, said that
the government will strive to sustain the Gross Domestic Product
(GDP) which has grown from 3.7 percent in 1995 to 6.3 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
Shamhuna said the government will ensure that all economic
sectors contribute to the efforts to boost economic growth during
1997/98. He also pledged to improve economic and social
infrastructure including water and electricity, road network and
telecommunications in a bid to raise the living conditions in the
rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
