<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cataract Menace Decried in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Fifty thousand Kenyans are
blinded by cataracts every year, local reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Forty percent of the blind patients in the eastern African
country suffer from cataracts, said Central Deputy Provincial
Commissioner Muli Malombe at the opening of a two-week cataract
surgery training session.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Fred Hollows Foundation of Australia, a
charitable organization, said at the session it will offer Kenya
medicine equipment and help the country train eye surgeons
especially in intraocular lens implants
</P>
<P>
The only known treatment for cataracts is surgery, which costs
about 80,000 Shillings (some 1481 U.S. Dollars) in the country's
private hospitals and 1,000 Shillings (46 Dollars) at Kenyatta
National Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Kenya now has about 38 eye surgeons (18 of them are
Nairobi-based) and 21 clinical officers specializing in this
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
