<HEADLINE> Only 2 Million Dollars of Medicine Arrives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat
Mubarak said today that only 2 million U.S. dollars worth of
medical supplies bought by Iraq under the "oil-for-food" deal has
arrived in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference here, Mubarak said that his
ministry has received only 2 million dollars worth of medical
supplies since the "oil-for-food" deal came into force in
December.
</P>
<P>
The "oil-for-food" deal, which was signed by Iraq and the
U.N. last May and has been renewed Monday, allows Iraq to sell 2
billion dollars worth of oil over six months to raise cash for
the humanitarian goods urgently needed in the country.
</P>
<P>
About 210 million dollars out of the total oil revenues is
earmarked for medicine and other medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
The delay of medical supplies has cost many lives of the
Iraqis, said Mubarak, adding that many of them could have been
saved if the medical supplies arrived in the country in time.
</P>
<P>
He said that the mortality rate among Iraqi children under
the age of five was 520 every month before the Gulf War, but it
has gone up to 4,212 as of last May.
</P>
<P>
He held the U.S. responsible for all this owing to its
obstruction of the medicine contracts signed by Iraq and foreign
companies under the deal.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said the U.S. representative to the U.N. Sanctions
Committee in charge of approving the contracts has held medicine
contracts related to epilepsy and cancer diseases as well as
other medicines used in surgical operations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. representative, the minister said, is blocking
contracts of medicine, which are very important for the treatment
of the current season diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
