<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders New Gun Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday ordered new regulations requiring licensed gun dealers
to post signs and give buyers written warnings against passing off
firearms to minors, in the hope to disarm teen gangs.
</P>
<P>
"I want every adult who buys a gun to see that sign and think
about it before they give a child a gun that could wind up in gang
violence," Clinton said in outlining the directive to be carried
out through formal Treasury Department rules.
</P>
<P>
The president was speaking at Georgetown University to a youth
violence conference of law enforcement officers, child advocates
and gun-control activists.
</P>
<P>
Although crime rates are generally on the decline for
successive years, Clinton cited Justice Department projections
that current trends, if left unchecked, will see juvenile arrests
for violent crimes more than double by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate is drafting juvenile crime legislation in the
wake of a House-passed bill that rebuffed several Clinton
initiatives opposed by the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
"A juvenile crime bill that doesn't crack down on guns and
gangs, that doesn't guarantee more prosecutors, more probation
officers and more `prevent programs' after school is a juvenile
crime bill in name only," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton had asked for stiffer penalties against adults
transferring guns to kids, an expansion of the Brady law to
prevent violent juveniles from owning firearms as adults and a
requirement that every gun sold be equipped with child safety
locks.
</P>
<P>
The administration cites 1995 statistics from the federal
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention that found that two in
25 high school students reported having carried a gun in the
previous 30 days.
</P>
<P>
The federal Bureau of Justice Statistics says handguns are the
leading cause of juvenile fatalities.
</P>
<P>
Clinton ordered that signs be posted at all handgun dealers
warning federal law prohibits the transfer of handguns to anyone
under age 18.
</P>
<P>
Some 124,000 gun dealers nationwide are regulated by the
Treasury Department's Bureau of Alcohol, tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
