<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Armed Forces today
urged the government to make great efforts to curb the rapidly
growing fundamentalist force in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Head of
Counter-Intelligence of the General Staff Fevzi Turkeri said that
the fundamentalists were trying to establish an Islamic system in
the secular republic.
</P>
<P>
He noted that these fundamental organizations were quickly
increasing their strength, adding their existence had constituted
"the most dangerous threat to Turkey's secularist system."
</P>
<P>
Turkeri complained that the current coalition government took a
weak stance against these organizations.
</P>
<P>
The military official noted that although the Armed Forces
were reluctant to be linked with the political affairs, they would
"not hesitate to carry out their Constitutional duty to defend the
country's secularism and democracy."
</P>
<P>
He also said that Islamic Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan
maintained warm contacts with some religious leaders known for
their fundamental words and deeds.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the military sources attending the news conference
openly accused Iran of supporting Turkey's fundamentalists, saying
Tehran wanted to see an Islamic regime to be established in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-Iranian relationship has seriously worsened during
the past months as a result of Ankara's accusation that Tehran
was exporting its Islamic revolution to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, Turkish military has been pressing
Erbakan-led coalition government to take tough measures against
the fundamentalist groups. 
</P>
