<HEADLINE> Britain Strives for Early N.Irish Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British Northern Ireland Secretary
Mo Mowlam said today the government would hold only one more
meeting with IRA's political wing Sinn Fein unless the guerrillas
announced a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"This is the time when we hope a settlement and final vote and
referendum could be held," Mowlam issued the warning to IRA in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"I think the talks are in danger of running into the sands and
I think progress must be made as soon as possible," she added.
</P>
<P>
The British Labor government eased a ban on official contacts
with Sinn Fein last month and two rounds of meetings have been
held so far. But Sinn Fein is banned from multi-party talks on the
future of the British-ruled province until the Irish Republican
Army announces a truce.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam said a request had been received on Tuesday for a third
meeting. The meeting would be held soon but it would be the last
one unless the IRA the ceasefire it broke in February 1996, she
underlined.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has launched military campaign for an end to the
British rule over the past 28 years. More than 3,000 people died
as a result of the violent conflicts between the IRA and the
government police.
</P>
<P>
"We will not go on indefinitely. We've no intention of doing
that at all... Another meeting is likely but that will be it," she
said. 
</P>
