<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President on Restructuring of National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 11 (Xinhua) --Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa today said that restructuring of the Tanzania National Bank
of Commerce (NBC) was imminent despite public outcry that the
decision was "engineered" by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
Addressing commanders of the Tanzania People's Defence Forces
(TPDF),President Mkapa said restructuring would rescue NBC from
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
He said the restructuring idea has been long overdue and it
was not a result of external pressure from IMF.
</P>
<P>
"The idea is not new, it was first floated in 1990 by Nyirabu
(Banking) Commission," said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
But he said that there was delay in working on the idea to
allow the commercial institution operate commercially.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1995, he said, the government took various
measures to re-organize the bank by injecting 198.1 billion
Tanzania Shillings (about 330 million US Dollars) to be used as
tax payers' money. Despite the measures, NBC operated below
profit line, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the present set up, NBC which was established in 1967,
would be burden to the government because it was too big to
manage, said the president.
</P>
<P>
When restructured, NBC will creat three subsidiaries, Trade
Bank, Regional Bank and Micro-finance Bank, each with differing
customer groups in the country. too big to manage.
</P>
<P>
He told that the introduction of private banks as a result of
the on-going economic reforms has threatened survival of NBC.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa further said his government would not inject
more money in NBC at the expense of other vital services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
