<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Threat to End Peacekeeping Forces' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. diplomat denied here today
that the United States has threatened to end the U.N. peacekeeping
forces' mission in Lebanon if a U.N. draft resolution requiring
Israel to pay war damages goes ahead.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe that we have done that," said Richard Jones,
the U.S. ambassador to Lebanon, after visiting Lebanese Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri in the latter's office.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the end of the meeting, the U.S. envoy
reiterated his country's support for the 4,500-strong U.N. interim
force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), quoting an earlier statement made by
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns.
</P>
<P>
Burns "stressed the support of the United States for the
peacekeeping forces and its role in keeping stability in the
region. This statement is very strong and I don't think its
necessary for me to say any more," Jones said.
</P>
<P>
On the draft resolution adopted last Saturday by the
U.N. general assembly's budgetary committee demanding Israel to
pay compensation for damages it caused to the UNIFIL last year,
the ambassador underlined that the issue is exclusively concerned
with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. general assembly will vote Friday to confirm the
committee resolution requiring Israel to pay more than 1.7
million U.S. dollars for damages resulting from its shelling of a
UNIFIL camp at the south Lebanese town of Qana on April 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I know that Lebanon is handling the issue as if it has
something to do with Qana. But in the view of the United
States, the issue is related to the United Nations especially
the international emergency forces operating in south Lebanon,"
the U.S. diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that it was a "very bad precedent" to ask a
certain country to pay compensation for an operation related
to the United Nations and "it has never taken place in the
United Nations' history."
</P>
<P>
Beirut media quoted U.S. delegate to the U.N. Linda Shenwick
as saying that "the adoption of the draft would make it hard for
Israel or the United States to support the force and make it
difficult for the United States to approve the extension of
UNIFIL's mandate next month."
</P>
<P>
Burns told a news briefing in Washington earlier this week
that it was "beyond the competence of the fifth committee to take
the decisions... fundamentally involving issues of international
peace and security, which are the primary responsibility of the
Security Council." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
