<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Plans to Review Surrogacy Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British Health Minister Tessa
Jowell said today the government was ready to review laws
governing surrogate motherhood following a number of controversial
cases in the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that in an area as sensitive as surrogacy the
law is kept under review in order to ensure that it continues to
meet public concerns," Jowell told a parliamentary questioner.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, a three-member team will assess
whether payment for surrogacy, including expenses, should be
allowed, whether changes are needed in the current laws and
whether surrogacy arrangements should be regulated through a
government body.
</P>
<P>
"We have specifically asked the review team to consider the
issue within the context that surrogacy should not be
commercialized and that any woman who has a baby as part of a
surrogacy arrangement should not be compelled to give it up if she
changes her mind," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, a few controversial surrogate cases
have happened in Britain, causing pressure for the revision of the
law on the surrogate motherhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
