<HEADLINE> Lesotho MPs Boycott Legitimatization of LCD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-two parliament
members of ruling Basutoland Congress Party (BCP) walked out of
National Assembly today, saying the speaker had legitimised a
coup by Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle on Monday announced the formation of a new party --
the Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD), and immediately
transferred the government power to the party.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle said the new party had controlled a majority of
parliament with the support of 41 of 64 parliament members.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the BCP, which tried to expel Mokhehle as
leader, condemned the move as a "coup d'etat".
</P>
<P>
Some extra-parliament parties, including the Basutho National
Party and the National Progressive Party, also condemned the
move, which they termed unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
The walkout of BCP parliament members took place just before
the tabling of a motion of confidence in Mokhehle and his new
government by Lesotho Deputy Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili,
who is also deputy leader of the LCD.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the walkout, some BCP members questioned Parliament
Speaker Teboho Kolane why he was legitimizing the unlawful
actions taken by Mokhehle, BCP National Executive member Tshiliso
Makhakhe told reporters.
</P>
<P>
BCP members were demanding a normal swearing-in process for
members of the new party, inclduing the prime minister, as well
as notification of the changes to the King Letsie III, Makhakhe
said.
</P>
<P>
There were several attacks by members of the BCP against the
speaker, accusing him of bias, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lesotho Information and Broadcasting Minister
Monyane Moleleki said today that threats by oppostion MPs to make
the National Assembly unworkable would not materialize.
</P>
<P>
"Their absence will make partliamentary work even more
comfortable without unnecessary noise and hackling," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
