<HEADLINE> Mbeki Blames Whites for Resisting Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki has said that political transformation from
apartheid in the country is close to stalling because of
resistance by whites.
</P>
<P>
There was a growing tendency among whites to blame blacks for
the failures of the first Government of National Reconciliation,
Mbeki told the parliament yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki pointed out that corruption caused by three centuries of
white domination was to blame for social inequalities which he
said have been escalating crime, corruption and a lack of values.
</P>
<P>
South Africa could not build a sound moral foundation while
whites continued to insist that apartheid was harmless, Mbeki
said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also criticized the white for their hostility towards
Archbishop Desmond Tutu's Truth and Reconciliation Commission,
which is empowered to pardon offenders who freely confess to
human rights offenses committed during the apartheid era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
