<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Steps up Pace in Implementing Arab Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will hold a series of meetings
with its Arab neighbors on launching joint free zones in a bid to
expedite the establishment of the Arab common market, the Egyptian
MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Khaled Hamdi, first undersecretary of the Egyptian
Ministry of Trade and Supply and head of the Trade Representation
Board, was quoted as saying that the joint Egyptian-Libyan
committee will meet shortly for such a purpose.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Moroccan Ministry of Trade Undersecretary
Fathallah al Segelmasi will pay a visit here on June 19 also to
discuss a bilateral free-trade zone.
</P>
<P>
More meetings with Yemni, Syrian, and Saudi officials on the
Arab common market are also on the agenda, according to Hamdi.
</P>
<P>
An agreement will be signed before the end of the year on
setting up a free-trade zone with Tunisia, Hamdi said, adding that
plans are in the works to create a similar zone with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Hamdi complained that the volume of trade between Egypt and
other Arab countries remains small in view of the potentials on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
Egypt exports to Arab countries total 1.6 billion pounds 0.47
billion U.S. dollars) annually while its imports account for 1.5
billion pounds 0.44 billion dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inter-Arab trade volume accounts for merely 7
percent of Arab countries' foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
