<HEADLINE> Greece Favors Relaxed Interpretation of Maastricht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Greece would support a proposal
for a more relaxed interpretation of the European Union's
Maastricht criteria, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing, Reppas said that if the criteria
were relaxed, his country should be included and participation in
the European Monetary Union (EMU) should have the same terms for
the first and second waves of entrants.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the statement by German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel to call for a supplement to the revised Maastricht treaty
containing measures to boost employment and social cohesion.
</P>
<P>
For years, Greece has been striving hard to develop its economy
with the aim of taking part in the first or second stage of the
European single currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
