<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon announced today that import duties on cars
will be raised. The decision was taken at an extraordinary cabinet
session Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Fuad Sinyoura, minister of state for financial affairs, said
that new cars with a value of 10,000 U.S. dollars or less will
have 20 percent duty.
</P>
<P>
More expensive cars, costing between 10,000 dollars and 32,500
dollars, carry a 50 percent tax, which doubles to 100 percent for
cars priced between 32,500 dollars and 65,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The customs duty on luxury cars costing more than 65,000
dollars is set at 200 percent, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan today expressed willingness to expand economic
cooperation with Qatar, a Gulf nation that severed ties with the
kingdom during the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The integration of economic construction with human dimension
should be emphasized and the Jordanian-Qatari cooperation is one
aspect of the integration, said Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan while
meeting a Qatari businessmen delegation here today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation headed by Board Chairman of Qatar's National
Hotels Company Sheikh Abdullah Ben Ahmad Al Thani, arrived here
yesterday on a 5-day visit to seek investment opportunities in the
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Thani said that Qatar is interested in
setting up joint ventures with Jordan, especially in the tourism
sector.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is one of Jordan's pillar industry. It earned 600
million U.S. dollars a year in the 1980s, some 10 percent of the
kingdom's gross national product.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ensour
briefed the delegation on the government's investment policy and
the strategy to promote the private sector's role in the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
The delegation met Jordanian Minister of Tourism and
Antiquities Akel Beltaji yesterday and will hold further talks
with Jordan's trade and economic representatives in the coming
days.
</P>
<P>
Qatar severed its relations with Jordan after the Gulf Crisis
broke out for Jordan sided with Iraq. When Jordan later distanced
itself away from Iraq to end international isolation, Qatar began
to restore touch in various sectors with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's exports to Qatar reached some 25 million U.S. dollars
in 1996 compared with about 14 million dollars in the previous
year, according to a report of the Amman Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Qatar exported some 8 million U.S. dollars worth of goods to
Jordan in 1996 compared with 9 million dollars in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will hold a series of meetings with its Arab
neighbors on launching joint free zones in a bid to expedite the
establishment of the Arab common market, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Khaled Hamdi, first undersecretary of the Egyptian
Ministry of Trade and Supply and head of the Trade Representation
Board, was quoted as saying that the joint Egyptian-Libyan
committee will meet shortly for such a purpose.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Moroccan Ministry of Trade Undersecretary
Fathallah al Segelmasi will pay a visit here on June 19 also to
discuss a bilateral free-trade zone.
</P>
<P>
More meetings with Yemni, Syrian, and Saudi officials on the
Arab common market are also on the agenda, according to Hamdi.
</P>
<P>
An agreement will be signed before the end of the year on
setting up a free-trade zone with Tunisia, Hamdi said, adding that
plans are in the works to create a similar zone with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Hamdi complained that the volume of trade between Egypt and
other Arab countries remains small in view of the potentials on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
Egypt exports to Arab countries total 1.6 billion pounds 0.47
billion U.S. dollars) annually while its imports account for 1.5
billion pounds 0.44 billion dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inter-Arab trade volume accounts for merely 7
percent of Arab countries' foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
