<HEADLINE> Chirac, Blair Agree On European Socio-Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac and
visiting British Prime Minister Tony Blair today agreed that the
European construction should first of all concentrate upon the key
economic and social questions faced by Europe.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Blair this afternoon at the Elysee
presidential palace, Chirac denied that he has changed attitude
toward European integration by emphasizing more on social aspects
and employment than monetary and financial aspects.
</P>
<P>
"I have not changed my view. I agree with the present requests
of the French government (of Lionel Jospin). There should also be
a coordination of economic policies (among European countries) and
on this point we should also make progress," said Chirac during a
brief meeting with the press.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government of Prime Minister Jospin has asked the
European Union (EU) to add a chapter on employment and
coordination of economic policy into the Stability Pact on the
future European single currency.
</P>
<P>
"It is nevertheless the case that Europe is not only a
financial and monetary problem, but also one of men and women who
need to be respected and taken into account," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also said that he thought the Stability Pact would be
ratified at the EU Amsterdam summit to be held next Monday and
Tuesday. He said that France, now under cohabitation of
government, would speak "with one voice" at the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
