<HEADLINE> US Issues Counterterrorism Reward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. today reissued a two
million U.S. dollar reward for information leading to the arrest
of people who committed terrorist acts against U.S. citizens in
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government is renewing its appeals to the Greek people
for information regarding terrorism against Americans under a
counterterrorism rewards program in close cooperation with the
Greek government, State Department Spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Four Americans were murdered in Athens in the past 22 years
while 28 others were injured in the terrorism incidents, according
to Burns. A Greek shipbuilder was assassinated in the Greek
capital two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
In February 1996, the American embassy in Athens was attacked
by a rocket and the U.S. issued the reward for help to capture the
people who did it.
</P>
<P>
"We have paid out over 5 million U.S. dollars over the last
decade or so in rewards to people all around the world... who have
helped us to capture terrorists," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"We have not forgotten about the four Americans who died in
Athens over the last 22 years," he added. "We will not forget
about them until the Greek government and the American government
and others around the world can locate the people who murdered
them and bring them to justice." 
</P>
</TEXT>
