<HEADLINE> Emir of Qatar Urges US to Improve Ties With Iran, Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Emir of Qatar today urged
U.S. President Bill Clinton to reconsider the strategy of "dual
containment" of Iran and Iraq and to improve relations with the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Qatari Foreign Minister Hamad bin Jasmin told reporters that
the Emir, Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani, raised the point in
an oval office when he met with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton "respected the Emir's ideas," but he
acknowledged the two leaders had "different opinions" on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
The Emir, who is in Washington to promote a Middle East
economic summit in Qatar's capital in November, told the
Washington Post in an interview published today that he could not
endorse the "dual containment" of Qatar's two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran's recently-held presidential elections meant the
United States had "no more excuses" for its policy toward Iran and
"communication with Iraq is better for the United States and
better for the area."
</P>
<P>
On Iraq, the Emir said the Iraqi people had suffered enough
because of U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
But the Emir's proposals were rebuffed and the White House said
the United States would stick to the "dual containment" strategy.
</P>
<P>
"We think our strategy... is a correct one," White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
